Dear Kitty,

I spent the entire day on Thursday with my friends. On Friday, we had guests over, and it continued like that until today. Throughout this past week, I have become very acquainted with Hello, and he has shared a significant amount about his life with me. He hails from Gelsenkirchen and currently resides with his grandparents.
Despite his parents being in Belgium, he is unable to travel there. Greetings! He was once in a relationship with a girl named Ursula, whom I also happen to know.

She is incredibly sweet and utterly dull. Since meeting me, Hello has come to the realization that he has been dozing off by Ursul's side. Therefore, I am like a revitalizing tonic. Please rephrase this passage.
It's impossible to predict one's true abilities! Jacque was at my place on Saturday night, but on Sunday afternoon she was at Hanneli's, leaving me feeling extremely bored.

Hello was meant to visit later that evening, however, he phoned at approximately six o'clock. I picked up the phone and he introduced himself as Helmuth Silberberg. He then requested, "Could I speak with Anne, please?"

"Hello there. This is Anne speaking."
"Hi Anne, how are you doing?"
"I'm doing well, thank you."
"I wanted to apologize, but I won't be able to join you tonight. However, I would really appreciate the opportunity to have a conversation with you."

Is it okay if I swing by and collect you in approximately ten minutes?

"Great, I'll be there shortly. Goodbye!"

I replied, "Oh, I wasn't aware of that."

"No, it wasn't anything like that. I explained to Ursul that we weren't compatible and it would be better if we didn't continue going out together. However, I assured her that she was still welcome at my house and I hoped that I would still be welcome at hers.

Please rephrase this text.

The recent events have been incredibly tumultuous, as if the entire world has been completely upended. Nevertheless, as you can see, Kit ty, I have managed to survive, and that is what matters most, according to Father. I am indeed alive, although please refrain from asking about my whereabouts or the circumstances surrounding it.

I will start by explaining what occurred on Sunday afternoon, although I suspect you may not comprehend my words today. 
Around three o'clock, someone rang the doorbell. As I was relaxing on the balcony, engrossed in a book and basking in the sunlight, I did not hear it.
A short time later, Margot came into the kitchen looking extremely upset. "Father has just received a notice from the SS," she whispered anxiously. "Mother has gone to speak with Mr.
I was in shock. A call-up: it's widely understood what that entails.

Thoughts of concentration camps and solitary cells overwhelmed me. How could we have allowed Father to face such a dreadful destiny? "There is no way he is going," Margot affirmed while we patiently waited for Mother in the living room.
My mother has gone to Mr. van Daan to inquire about the possibility of relocating to our hiding place tomorrow. The van Daans will be accompanying us.

We will be a total of seven individuals. Silence fell upon us, rendering us unable to utter a word. The idea of our father being away, visiting someone at the Jewish Hospital without any knowledge of the events unfolding, the prolonged anticipation for our mother's return, the oppressive heat, and the overwhelming tension—these circumstances left us speechless.

The doorbell rang once more out of the blue. "That must be Hello," I remarked. 
"Please refrain from opening the door!" Margot exclaimed urgently to prevent me from doing so.

However, it turned out to be unnecessary as we could hear Mother and Mr. van Daan conversing downstairs with Hello, and subsequently, they entered and closed the door. Whenever the bell rang, either Margot or I had to quietly descend the stairs to check if it was Father, and we did not allow anyone else to enter.

Margot and I were asked to leave the room so that Mr. van Daan could speak to Mother in private. 
While we were sitting in our bedroom, Margot confided in me that the call-up was meant for her, not Father. 
Could you please paraphrase this passage?

I started crying as the second shock hit me. It seems that sixteen-year-old girls like Margot are being sent away alone. But thankfully, Margot won't be going; Mother had confirmed it, which I think is what Father meant when he discussed us going into hiding.
Where should we hide? Should we hide in the city or in the country?
Can you please rephrase this text?

I had so many questions running through my mind, but I wasn't permitted to ask them. Despite this, Margot and I began packing our most essential items into a schoolbag. The first item I placed inside was my diary, followed by curlers, handkerchiefs, schoolbooks, a comb, and a few old letters.

I filled the bag with the most bizarre items, consumed by the idea of going into hiding, but I have no regrets. Memories hold greater significance to me than clothing. Eventually, Father arrived home at approximately five o'clock, and we contacted Mr.
Kleiman was asked if he could come by that evening, so Mr. van Daan left to fetch Mi ep.

Miep appeared and assured us that she would be back later that evening, carrying a bag filled with shoes, dresses, jackets, underwear, and stockings. Following her departure, our apartment fell into silence and none of us had any appetite. The atmosphere remained uncomfortably warm, and there was an unsettling sense of unfamiliarity in the air.

We had given our large upstairs room on rent to a Mr. Goldschmidt, a man in his thirties who had been divorced. It seemed like he had no plans for the evening, as he stayed until ten o'clock despite our subtle suggestions for him to leave. Miep and Jan Gies arrived at eleven.

Miep, who has been employed by Father's company since 1933, has developed a strong friendship, as has her husband Jan. Once more, Miep's bag and Jan's deep pockets became the hiding places for shoes, stockings, books, and underwear. At eleven-thirty, they also vanished.

Despite my exhaustion, I easily fell asleep and didn't wake up until Mother called me at five-thirty in the morning, which happened to be my last night in my own bed. Luckily, the weather was more bearable than the previous Sunday as a gentle rain provided warmth throughout the day.

We were all bundled up in numerous layers of clothing, making it seem like we were about to spend the night in a freezer. We did this so that we could bring along extra clothes. No Jewish person in our position would risk leaving the house with a suitcase filled with clothes. I had on two undershirts, three sets of underpants, a dress, and on top of that, a skirt, a jacket, a raincoat, two pairs of stockings, sturdy shoes, a hat, a scarf, and many other items.

Before we even left the house, I felt suffocated, but nobody bothered to inquire about my well-being. Margot packed her schoolbag with books, retrieved her bicycle, and followed Miep's lead as we ventured into the vast unknown. That's how I perceived it anyway, as I still remained unaware of the location of our hiding spot.

We closed the door behind us at seven-thirty, bidding farewell only to Moortje, my cat. We left a note for Mr. Goldschmidt, instructing him to take her to our neighbors, who would provide her with a loving home.

The beds with no sheets, the breakfast items left on the table, and the pound of meat for the cat in the kitchen gave the appearance that we had left hastily. However, our focus was not on appearances; our only desire was to escape that place and reach our destination without any harm.
The only thing that mattered was the three of us walking in the heavy rain, carrying schoolbags and shopping bags brimming with a wide assortment of items.

The sympathetic glances from the individuals commuting to work at such an early time indicated their regretful inability to provide us with any form of transportation; the prominent yellow star on our clothing made it evident. It was only as we strolled down the street that Father and Mother gradually disclosed the details of the plan. Over the past few months, we had been steadily removing furniture and clothing from our apartment.

On July 16, we had initially planned to go into hiding. However, due to Margot's call-up notice, we had to change our plan and move it up by ten days. As a result, we had to accept the fact that our rooms would be less organized.

The hiding place was situated within Father's office building. This may be difficult for those unfamiliar with the situation to comprehend, so allow me to provide an explanation. Father's office had a small staff, primarily consisting of just Mr.
Kugler, Mr. Kleiman, Miep, and a typist named Bep Voskuijl, who was twenty-three years old, were all given notice of our arrival. Mr.

Bep's father, Voskuijl, is employed in the warehouse where he works alongside two assistants. Neither of the assistants were given any information. 
The building is described as a large warehouse located on the ground floor. It serves as a workroom and storage area and is divided into various sections, including the stockroom and the milling room. In the milling room, cinnamon, cloves, and a substitute for pepper are ground.

Adjacent to the warehouse doors, there is an additional external door that serves as a separate entrance to the office. Immediately inside the office door, there is another door, which leads to a staircase. Upon reaching the top of the stairs, there is yet another door with a frosted window displaying the word "Office" in black lettering.
The front office is spacious, bright, and bustling with activity. Bep, Miep, and Mr. Kleiman are the individuals who work there throughout the day.

Upon entering an alcove, which houses a safe, a wardrobe, and a generously stocked cupboard, you arrive at a small, dimly lit, and poorly ventilated back office. Previously, this space was jointly utilized by Mr. Kugler and Mr. [Unknown].
Van Daan used to live in the van, but now it is solely occupied by Mr. Kugler.

You can access Kugler's office from the hallway, but only through a glass door that can be opened from the inside, not easily from the outside. If you exit Mr. Kugler's office and walk through the long, narrow hallway past the coal bin, you will encounter four steps that lead to the private office, which is the highlight of the entire building.

The second floor features elegant mahogany furniture, complemented by a linoleum floor adorned with throw rugs. The room is equipped with a radio and a sophisticated lamp, exuding a sense of luxury. Adjacent to this room is a spacious kitchen, complete with a hot-water heater and two gas burners. Additionally, there is a bathroom located nearby.

There is a wooden staircase that goes from the downstairs hallway to the third floor. When you reach the top of the stairs, there is a landing with doors on both sides. The door on the left leads to the spice storage area, attic, and loft in the front part of the house.

There is a characteristic Dutch feature in the house - a steep staircase that can easily cause ankle injuries. This staircase leads from the front part of the house to another door that opens onto the street. On the right side of the landing, there is a door that provides access to the "Secret Annex" located at the rear of the house. The plain gray door conceals the surprising number of rooms hidden behind it.

Upon reaching the door, you will encounter a single small step, and once you cross it, you will find yourself inside. Directly in front of you, there will be a steep flight of stairs. On the left side, there is a narrow hallway that leads to a room utilized as the living area for the Frank family.

There is a room and a bedroom. Adjacent to them is a smaller room, which serves as both the bedroom and study for the two young ladies in the family. On the right side of the stairs, there is a washroom without any windows.

There is a link provided. The door situated in the corner leads to the bathroom, while another door leads to the room shared by Margot and myself. If you ascend the stairs and open the door at the top, you will be pleasantly surprised by the size, brightness, and spaciousness of the room in an old house located by the canalside.
The room includes a stove (originating from Mr. Kugler's laboratory) and a sink, serving as both the kitchen and bedroom of Mr.
The living room, dining room, and study will be shared by Mr. and Mrs. van Daan, as well as the rest of us. Additionally, there will be a small separate room designated as Peter van Daan's bedroom.
In addition to the front part of the building, there is also an attic and a loft. That's the whole layout of our beautiful Annex! Now you have been acquainted with all of it.

I apologize for potentially boring you with the lengthy description of our house, but I believe it's important for you to know where I am. The reason behind my current location will be explained in my upcoming letters. However, let me continue my story. As I mentioned before, I hadn't finished describing our journey. Once we reached 263 Prinsengracht, Miep promptly guided us through the extensive hallway and up the wooden staircase to the floor above, where the Annex is located.

After we entered, she closed the door, leaving us alone. Margot had arrived earlier on her bicycle and was patiently waiting for us. The abundance of belongings in our living room and the rest of the house was indescribable.

The office was cluttered with cardboard boxes that had been delivered over the past few months. They were stacked on the floors and beds. The small room was completely filled with linens from the floor to the ceiling. If we wished to sleep in well-arranged beds that night, we needed to start organizing the chaotic situation.

Mother and Margot were completely immobile. They rested on their simple mattresses, exhausted, unhappy, and who knows what else. However, Father and I, the two individuals responsible for tidying up in the family, immediately began working.

Throughout the entire day, we tirelessly unloaded boxes, stocked cupboards, hammered nails, and organized the chaos, until we finally collapsed into our freshly made beds at night, completely drained. We hadn't managed to have a warm meal all day, but it didn't bother us; Mother and Margot were too exhausted and anxious to eat, while Father and I were preoccupied with our tasks.

On Tuesday morning, we resumed our activities from the previous night. Bep and Miep went to the grocery store with our ration coupons while Father focused on our blackout screens. We diligently scrubbed the kitchen floor and remained occupied from morning till night. It wasn't until Wednesday that I had the opportunity to contemplate the immense transformation in my life.

On this Saturday, July 11, 1942, I finally had a moment to share with you all what had happened to me since our arrival in the Secret Annex. It was a time for reflection, as I realized the significance of my experiences and what was yet to come. 
With love, Anne 

Dearest Kitty, 

Father, Mother, and Margot still struggle to adjust to the chiming of the Westertoren clock, which reminds us of the time every fifteen minutes. However, I, on the other hand, have taken a liking to it right from the beginning. The sound brings me comfort, especially during the night.

Undoubtedly, you are curious about my thoughts on being in hiding. To be honest, I am still uncertain about my feelings towards it. Although I don't believe I will ever truly feel comfortable in this house, it doesn't necessarily mean that I despise it.

It feels more like being on a vacation at a peculiar boarding house. It may seem strange to perceive life in hiding this way, but that's the reality of the situation. The Annex provides an excellent location for concealment.
Although it may be damp and uneven, there is likely no more cozy hiding spot in Amsterdam, or even in all of Holland. Until now, our bedroom has been quite empty with its plain walls.

Thanks to my father, who had brought my entire collection of postcards and movie-star pictures with him beforehand, I was able to cover the walls with pictures using a brush and a pot of glue. The result is a much more cheerful atmosphere. Once the van Daans arrive, we will be able to construct cupboards and other miscellaneous items using the wood that is stacked in the attic.

Yesterday, Mother and Margot experienced some improvement in their health. Mother's well-being allowed her to attempt cooking split-pea soup for the first time. However, while she was downstairs talking, she completely forgot about it. As a result, the beans became burnt to a black color, and no matter how much scraping was done, they couldn't be removed from the pan.

Yesterday evening, the four of us ventured to the secluded office and tuned in to the radio broadcast from England. The fear of being overheard consumed me, leading me to plead with Father to accompany me back upstairs. Mother sympathized with my unease and accompanied me as well.

Regardless of what we do, we are extremely concerned about the possibility of our neighbors overhearing or observing us. We began right away on the very first day by sewing curtains. However, it would be quite a stretch to refer to them as such, as they are merely remnants of fabric that differ significantly in shape, quality, and pattern. Father and I clumsily stitched them together with our unskilled hands.

The windows will be our hiding place until we emerge. To our right is a Keg Company branch, a firm hailing from Zaandam, and on our left is a furniture workshop. Although the workers are not present after hours, any noise we generate could potentially pass through the walls.

We have prohibited Margot from coughing during the night, despite her having a severe cold, and we are administering high doses of codeine to her. I am eagerly anticipating the arrival of the van Daans, scheduled for Tuesday. It will bring more enjoyment and alleviate the silence.

The evenings and nights make me extremely anxious because of the unsettling silence. I would do anything to have one of our helpers stay overnight. Fortunately, things are not too terrible here as we are able to cook for ourselves and listen to the radio in my father's office.

Kleiman, Miep, and Bep Voskuijl have provided us with significant assistance. We have already preserved a large quantity of rhubarb, strawberries, and cherries, so we are unlikely to experience boredom for now. Additionally, we have a collection of reading materials and plan to purchase numerous games.

Naturally, we are unable to gaze out of the window or venture outside. Additionally, we must maintain silence to ensure that the individuals residing below are not able to detect our presence. Our day before was quite eventful.
Mr. Kugler required us to separate two crates of cherries for canning. The empty crates will be repurposed to create bookshelves.

I am receiving a phone call. 
Sincerely, Anne 
COMMENT ADDED BY ANNE ON SEPTEMBER 2g, 1942: My inability to go outside is causing me great distress, and I am filled with fear that our secret hiding place will be found, resulting in our execution. Naturally, this is a very bleak possibility.

Despite the kindness I have received from everyone due to my recent birthday, I find myself growing more distant from Mother and Margo each day. Despite their initial praise, they quickly revert to criticizing me shortly after. The contrast between their treatment of Margot and myself is evident.
For instance, due to Margot's actions, the vacuum cleaner was broken.

We had no electricity for the rest of the day because Margot had accidentally pulled the plug out by the cord. When Mother noticed, she commented, "Well, Margot, it's clear that you're not used to working, otherwise you would have known not to yank the plug out by the cord." Margot responded, and that was the end of the incident.

However, this afternoon, when I attempted to rewrite something on Mother's shopping list because her handwriting is difficult to decipher, she refused to let me.

Once again, she scolded me harshly, and the entire family ended up getting dragged into it. I don't belong with them, and this feeling has become evident to me in recent weeks. They are very emotional when they are together, but I prefer to be emotional in solitude.

People often comment on how well the four of us get along and how pleasant it is, but they never consider that I don't share the same sentiment. Daddy is the only one who truly comprehends me, although he usually supports Mother and Margot. It really annoys me when they discuss me in front of others, recounting my moments of crying or praising my sensible behavior.
This is really terrible. Moreover, the mention of Moortje is particularly distressing for me as it hits me right in the heart.

I constantly miss her throughout the day, and nobody is aware of how frequently she crosses my mind; whenever thoughts of her arise, my eyes well up with tears. Moortje is incredibly dear to me, and my love for her is so strong that I cannot help but hope for her return. Although I have many dreams, the harsh reality is that we must remain here until the war concludes.
It is not possible for us to go outside at any time, and the only individuals who are allowed to visit us are Miep, her husband Jan, Bep Voskuijl, Mr. Voskuijl, Mr. Kugler, and Mr.
Kleiman and Mrs. Kleiman did not attend as Mrs. Kleiman believed it to be too dangerous. Anne added a comment in September 1942 stating that her father is always very kind.

He comprehends me completely, and I desire to have a sincere and personal conversation with him at some point without immediately breaking down in tears. However, it seems that my emotional response is related to my age. Although I have a strong inclination to dedicate all my time to writing, I acknowledge that it may become monotonous.

Until now, I have solely shared my thoughts with my personal journal. However, I have yet to find the opportunity to compose amusing anecdotes that I can perform for an audience at a later time. Moving forward, I plan to allocate less time to sentimental musings and focus more on portraying the truth of reality.

Dear Kitty, 
I apologize for being absent for a whole month, but so little has occurred that I can't find much to share.

The van Daans arrived on July 13th, a day earlier than expected. Initially, we had anticipated their arrival on the fourteenth. However, due to the widespread issuance of call-up notices by the Germans from the thirteenth to the sixteenth, causing significant unrest, they chose to err on the side of caution and depart a day in advance rather than risk being delayed.

Peter van Daan arrived at nine-thirty in the morning, which was during our breakfast time. Peter, who is nearly sixteen years old, is a shy and awkward boy whose presence is not expected to make a significant impact.
Mrs. van Daan arrived thirty minutes after we did, which amused us greatly.

Van Daan was holding a hatbox containing a sizable chamber pot. She expressed, "I simply don't feel comfortable without my chamber pot," and promptly placed it under the divan as the first item to be permanently stored there. Instead of a chamber pot, Mr. [last name] had something else in his possession.

Van D. carried a collapsible tea table with him. 
From the beginning, we shared our meals and within three days, it seemed like the seven of us had formed a close-knit family.
The van Daans had a lot to share about the week we had spent away from society. We were particularly curious about what had occurred with our apartment and Mr. Goldschmidt.
On Monday morning at nine, Mr. Goldschmidt gave me a call and requested my presence at his place.
I immediately sought out Mr. Goldschmidt, who appeared extremely upset. He presented me with a note left behind by the Frank family.

As per the instructions, he intended to take the cat to our neighbors, which I concurred was a wise decision. He was concerned that our house might be inspected, so we meticulously tidied up each room and removed the breakfast items from the table. Unexpectedly, I noticed a notebook on Mrs. [last name]'s desk.

I feigned surprise and horror when I saw the address in Maastricht written on Frank's desk, knowing full well that Mrs. Frank had intentionally left it there. I then pleaded with Mr. to do something about it.
Goldschmidt intends to burn this piece of paper that holds incriminating evidence. I strongly denied having any knowledge of your disappearance, but the note sparked an idea in my mind. 'Mr.
"Goldschmidt," I said, "I bet I know the significance of this address. Approximately half a year ago, a senior officer paid a visit to the office. It appears that he and Mr. [surname]..."
Frank and Mr. Frank grew up together and Frank made a promise to help him if the need ever arose.

If I remember correctly, he was stationed in Maastricht. It appears that this officer has honored his promise and is strategizing a way to assist them in reaching Belgium and eventually Switzerland. It is safe to share this information with any acquaintances or individuals inquiring about the Franks' whereabouts.

Certainly, there's no need to include the part about Maastricht. 
And then, I departed. This is the tale that has been shared with most of your friends, as I later heard it from multiple sources." 
We found it incredibly amusing, but our laughter grew even louder when Mr. van Daan mentioned that some individuals possess quite imaginative minds.

Our neighbors have reported seeing all four of us riding on our bikes early in the morning, while another woman is convinced that we were loaded onto a military vehicle in the middle of the night. It seems that our hiding place in the Secret Annex has become even more secure. This is because the authorities are searching houses for hidden bicycles.

Kugler believed that it would be more advantageous to have a bookcase constructed in the vicinity of the entrance to our concealed location. This bookcase is designed to pivot on its hinges and function as a door.

Voskuijl was responsible for the carpentry tasks, and he has been informed about our group of seven individuals in hiding. He has been incredibly helpful to us. Currently, whenever we need to go downstairs, we have to crouch and then leap.

Following the initial three days, we all had bumps on our foreheads due to repeatedly hitting them against the low doorway. However, Peter attempted to alleviate this issue by securing a towel filled with wood shavings onto the frame of the door. Let's observe if this solution proves effective!

I currently have a break from schoolwork and have decided to take a vacation until September. My father plans to begin tutoring me at that time, but we need to purchase all the necessary books beforehand.
There hasn't been much of a difference in our daily routines. Peter got his hair cut today, but it's not anything out of the ordinary. Mr.
Van Daan and I frequently clash with each other. Mama consistently treats me as if I am still a baby, a behavior that I find intolerable. However, besides these issues, everything else is improving.

I believe Peter has not shown any improvement in his behavior. He is an unpleasant boy who spends most of his time lying on his bed, only occasionally getting up to do some carpentry before going back to sleep. He is quite foolish!

This morning, Mama delivered another one of her terrible sermons to me. We always seem to have contrasting opinions on everything. Daddy is such a kind person; he may get angry with me, but it never lasts for more than five minutes.
Despite everything, we manage to make the most of the beautiful weather outside by relaxing on the folding bed in the attic on this hot day. - Anne
COMMENT ADDED BY ANNE ON SEPTEMBER 21, 1942: Lately, Mr. van Daan has been extremely pleasant towards me. I haven't mentioned it, but I've been enjoying his kindness while it continues.

Dear Kitty, 
There has been a terrible argument between Mr. and Mrs. van Daan.

I have never witnessed anything similar before, given that my parents would never argue with each other in such a manner. The disagreement revolved around something so insignificant that it didn't appear to be worth discussing at all. Anyway, everyone is entitled to their own opinions and preferences. Kindly rephrase this passage.

It is indeed challenging for Peter, as he finds himself stuck in a difficult situation. However, people no longer regard Peter as credible due to his excessive sensitivity and laziness. Yesterday, he was extremely anxious because his tongue turned blue instead of its usual pink color. This unusual occurrence vanished as suddenly as it appeared.

Currently, he is strolling with a weighty scarf draped around his neck due to experiencing stiffness. Additionally, His Highness has expressed discomfort from lumbago. Experiencing aches and pains in his heart, kidneys, and lungs is a common occurrence as well.

He is a complete hypochondriac! (Is that the correct word?)
There is tension between Mother and Mrs. van Daan. 
Could you please rephrase this text?
There are numerous reasons that contribute to the presence of friction. One specific example is Mrs. van D.

She has taken most of her sheets from our shared linen closet, leaving only three. She believes that mothers can be used by both families. However, she will be unpleasantly surprised when she realizes that Mother has also done the same.
In addition, Mrs. van D. is upset because we are using her china instead of our own.

She is currently attempting to discover the whereabouts of our plates; however, they are much closer than she assumes. They are securely packed in cardboard boxes in the attic, hidden behind a pile of Opekta advertising material. As long as we are in hiding, she will be unable to access the plates. This arrangement works well for me, considering my frequent accidents.
Yesterday, I accidentally shattered a soup bowl that belonged to Mrs. van D. In response, she exclaimed angrily, "Oh!"

"Could you please be more cautious? That was my final one." 
Please remember, Kitty, that the two women speak Dutch very poorly (I won't even mention the men: they would be deeply offended). If you were to hear their clumsy attempts, you would find it hilarious. 
Please provide an alternative wording.

We have stopped pointing out their mistakes because it doesn't make a difference when we correct them. Whenever I mention quotes from Mother or Mrs. van Daan, I will write in correct Dutch instead of attempting to imitate their speech.
Last week, our monotonous routine was momentarily disrupted by Peter and a book about women. It's important to clarify that Margo and Peter have permission to read almost all of Mr.'s books.
Kleiman loaned us the book, but the adults chose to keep it exclusively for themselves. Peter's curiosity was immediately piqued.
What was the forbidden fruit that it contained? When his mother was downstairs talking, he secretly took it and went to the loft. Everything was fine for two days. Please rephrase this text.
Mrs. van Daan was aware of his actions, but remained silent until Mr. van Daan discovered it.

After throwing a fit, he angrily snatched the book and believed that would be the end of the matter. However, he failed to consider his son's curiosity. Peter, unaffected by his father's hasty behavior, started brainstorming ideas to continue reading the incredibly captivating book.
Meanwhile, Mrs. van D. inquired Mother for her viewpoint.

Mother believed that this specific book was not appropriate for Margot, but she had no issue with letting her read the majority of other books. Mrs. van Daan, Mother explained, there is a notable distinction between Margot and Peter.

Firstly, Margot is a female, and it is commonly believed that females tend to be more mature than males. 
Secondly, she has already indulged in numerous serious books and does not actively seek out those that are no longer considered forbidden. 
Thirdly, Margot possesses a greater level of sensibility and intellectual advancement due to her attendance at a prestigious school for a duration of four years.

Van Daan shared the same opinion, believing it to be morally incorrect for young individuals to read literature intended for adults. On the other hand, Peter had identified an opportune moment when nobody would pay attention to him or the book. At seven-thirty in the evening, when the entire family was engrossed by the radio in the private office, he seized the opportunity to take his valued possession and quietly returned to the attic.

He was supposed to return by eight-thirty, but he was so absorbed in the book that he lost track of time. As he was descending the stairs, his father walked into the room. The ensuing events were predictable: a slap, a smack, and a struggle over the book, resulting in it being placed on the table and Peter being sent to the loft. This was the situation when it was time for the family meal.
Peter remained upstairs, unnoticed and forgotten, unable to enjoy his dinner. Meanwhile, the rest of us carried on eating and conversing happily, until a sharp whistle broke the tranquility.
Our forks were set aside as we locked eyes, the evident shock reflecting on our pale expressions. Suddenly, Peter's voice echoed down the chimney, declaring, "I refuse to descend!"

Mr. van Daan stood up suddenly, dropping his napkin onto the floor, and exclaimed loudly, his face turning red with anger, "I can't take it anymore!" 
Father, concerned about the potential consequences, quickly took hold of Mr. van Daan's arm and the two men went upstairs to the attic. There was a lot of resistance and kicking, but eventually Peter ended up in his room with the door closed, and the rest of us continued with our meal.
Mrs. van Daan desired to set aside a portion of bread for her beloved child, however Mr. van D.

He was firm. "Unless he apologizes immediately, he will be forced to sleep in the attic."
We argued that skipping dinner was punishment enough. What if Peter were to get sick?

It would not be possible for us to contact a doctor.
Peter did not offer an apology and went back to the loft.
Mister.

Van Daan chose not to interfere, but he did notice the following morning that Peter had slept in his bed. At seven o'clock, Peter returned to the attic, but Father managed to convince him to come downstairs with a few kind words. After three days of sulking and refusing to speak, everything returned to its usual state.

Dear Kitty, 
I want to update you on the current situation in the Annex. We have recently installed a lamp above my bed, which will allow me to switch on the light when I hear the sound of gunfire. Unfortunately, I am unable to use it at the moment as we have decided to keep our window slightly open, both during the day and at night.

The male individuals from the van Daan group have constructed a practical wooden pantry, treated with a dark stain, equipped with authentic screens to keep food safe. Previously, this magnificent cupboard was positioned in Peter's room, but to allow for better ventilation, it has been relocated to the attic. In its original spot, a shelf has now been installed.

I suggested to Peter that he should place his table below the shelf, incorporate a pleasant rug, and hang his own cupboard in the current location of the table. This could potentially enhance the coziness of his small space, although I personally wouldn't find it suitable for sleeping. Mrs.
Van Daan is unbearable. I constantly receive scolding for my continuous talking when I'm upstairs. However, I choose to disregard the scolding and let the words have no effect on me.

She has a new strategy to avoid washing the pots and pans: she purposely leaves a small amount of food in the bottom of the pan, allowing it to spoil rather than transferring it to a different dish. Later in the afternoon, when Margot is responsible for cleaning all the pots and pans, Madame sympathetically exclaims, "Oh, poor Margot, you have such a heavy workload!" This occurs every other week, with Mr. [last name] being exempt from this chore.

Kleiman delivers a few books that are specifically written for girls who are the same age as me. I am really excited about the loop ter Heul series. I have truly loved reading all of Cissy van Marxveldt's books.

I have reread The Zaniest Summer four times, and the absurd circumstances still bring me laughter. My father and I are presently engaged in tracing our family lineage, and he imparts information about each individual as we progress. I have also started my academic assignments.

I am putting in a lot of effort to learn French, memorizing five irregular verbs every day. However, I have unfortunately forgotten a significant amount of what I learned in school. Peter has reluctantly started practicing his English.

I have recently received some schoolbooks, and I have brought a plentiful amount of notebooks, pencils, erasers, and labels from my home. Pim (which is the nickname we use for Father) has asked me to assist him with his Dutch lessons. I am more than happy to teach him in return for his help with French and other subjects.

The beans flew through the air and cascaded down the stairs. As that particular sack contained approximately fifty pounds of beans, the resulting noise could easily wake the deceased.

They were certain that the house was collapsing around them as they descended the stairs. Peter was shocked, but then erupted into laughter upon seeing me standing at the foot of the stairs, resembling an isolated island amidst a vast expanse of brown beans, with waves of beans gently touching my ankles. Immediately, we started gathering them, but beans, being tiny and slippery, have a tendency to roll into every possible nook and cranny.

This situation wouldn't be as difficult if Mr. Dussel wasn't such a gossip and didn't specifically choose Mother as the person to share his reports with.

Dussel has just scolded me severely, and now my mother is lecturing me, going over the same points again, but this time using every argument in the book. If I'm particularly fortunate, Mrs. van D will also express her disapproval.

Five minutes later, I am called to account and confronted with strict rules! Being the poorly raised focal point of a family full of fault-finders is truly challenging. At night, when I reflect on my numerous transgressions and magnified deficiencies, the overwhelming number of things I must contemplate leaves me feeling perplexed. Depending on my emotional state, I either find myself laughing or crying.

As I drift off to sleep, I experience a peculiar sensation of desiring to be someone other than who I am or desiring to be different than what I want to be. It could even be a longing to act in ways that differ from my true self or desired behavior. I apologize if I am causing confusion, as I prefer not to strike through words, and discarding paper is considered unacceptable during times of scarcity.
I strongly discourage you from re-reading the previous passage and attempting to understand it fully, as it may lead to confusion and difficulty in finding a way out of it.

Dear Kitty, 
This year, Hanukkah and St. Nicholas Day were almost at the same time, only one day apart. We didn't make a big celebration for Hanukkah, just exchanging a few small presents and lighting the candles.

Due to the limited availability of candles, we only lit them for a duration of ten minutes. However, regardless of the time, as long as we sing the song, it doesn't matter. Mr. van Daan crafted a wooden menorah, resolving that concern as well.

Saturday's St. Nicholas Day was a lot more enjoyable. While we were having dinner, Bep and Miep were engrossed in secretive conversations with Father, which piqued our curiosity and made us suspect that they were plotting something.

As expected, we all went downstairs together at eight o'clock, making our way through the dark hallway (which made me feel uneasy, and I longed to be back upstairs where it was safe) and reached the alcove. Since this room lacks windows, we were able to turn on the light. Once that was done, Father proceeded to open the large cabinet.

"Wow, this is amazing!" we exclaimed together. 
Situated in the corner was a sizable basket adorned with vibrant paper and a Black Peter mask. 
Without hesitation, we swiftly brought the basket up to the upper level.

There was a small gift for each person inside, accompanied by a suitable verse. As you are familiar with the types of poems that people exchange on St. Nicholas Day, I will not transcribe them for you.

I was given a Kewpie doll, my father received bookends, and so on. Regardless, it was a thoughtful gesture, and since none of us had ever commemorated St. Nicholas Day before, this seemed like the perfect occasion to start.

Anne's letter ends with a postscript mentioning that there were presents for everyone downstairs, some leftovers from the past, and that Miep and Bep are always thankful for money. Additionally, they received news about Mr.
Mr. Voskuijl was the creator of Van Daan's ashtray, Mr. Dussel's picture frame, and Father's bookends.
I am amazed by how someone can possess such incredible dexterity and skill with their hands. It is truly a mystery to me!

Dearest Kitty,
Mr. van Daan had previous experience in the meat, sausage, and spice industry. He was initially hired for his expertise in spices, but to our pleasant surprise, his sausage-making skills have proven to be very useful now.
We secretly purchased a substantial quantity of meat with the intention of preserving it in case of future hardships. Mr. van Daan took it upon himself to create bratwurst, sausages, and mettwurst.

I enjoyed watching him grind the meat repeatedly using the grinder. After that, he combined the ground meat with the rest of the ingredients and used a long pipe to push the mixture into the casings. For lunch, we enjoyed the bratwurst with sauerkraut. However, the sausages, which were meant to be canned, needed to be dried first. Therefore, we hung them over a suspended pole to let them dry.
As soon as everyone entered the room, they couldn't help but burst into laughter upon seeing the sausages dangling. The sight was incredibly funny. The kitchen was a complete mess. Mr.

Van Daan, wearing his wife's apron and appearing larger than before, was busily working on the meat. With his hands covered in blood, his face red, and his apron spotted, he resembled a genuine butcher. Mrs.

D. was attempting to multitask: studying Dutch from a book, stirring the soup, keeping an eye on the meat, and expressing frustration over her broken rib. This is the result of her being overwhelmed and trying to do too many things at once.

Some women engage in foolish exercises to reduce the size of their buttocks. Dussel, who had an eye infection, sat near the stove, gently applying camomile tea to his eye. Pim, positioned in the only stream of sunlight from the window, continuously adjusted his chair to avoid the obstruction.

He seemed to be suffering from rheumatism as he had a slight hunch and a pained expression while keeping a watchful eye on Mr. van Daa n. He resembled the elderly individuals one often encounters in a destitute institution.

Peter and Mouschi, the cat, were playing energetically in the room, while Mother, Margot, and I were busy peeling boiled potatoes. In all honesty, none of us were fully focused on our tasks as we were all preoccupied with observing Mr. van Daan.

Dussel has recently started his dental practice. As a fun exercise, I will describe his first session with a patient. The patient's mother was in the middle of ironing, and Mrs. [last name] was present during the appointment.

While the rest of the audience burst into laughter, Mr. Dussel calmly watched the scene, his hands resting on his hips. It was undoubtedly unkind of us.

Finally, I succeeded in pulling the object out, and Mr. Dussel resumed his work without acknowledging what had just occurred. He was so efficient that Mrs. (last name) was unable to react.

Van D. and I executed our duties proficiently. The entire scenario bore a striking resemblance to one of those ancient engravings from the Middle Ages titled "A Quack at Work." Meanwhile, the patient grew increasingly agitated as she had to constantly monitor her soup and her food.
It is definite that Mrs. van D. will not be scheduling another dental appointment for quite some time.

I am currently sitting comfortably in the front office, observing people passing by through a small opening in the thick curtains. The lighting is dim, but sufficient enough for me to write. It feels quite peculiar to observe the individuals walking past.

The individuals appear to be in a rush, to the point where they almost stumble over themselves. The cyclists zoom by so swiftly that it becomes difficult to distinguish who is actually riding the bike. The residents of this community do not possess especially pleasing appearances.

The children, in particular, are extremely filthy. They are not someone you would want to come into contact with. These kids come from real slums and have runny noses. It is difficult for me to comprehend what they are saying.

During our bath yesterday afternoon, I proposed the idea of using a fishing rod to catch each passing child, placing them in the tub, and cleaning and repairing their clothes. Margot, however, pointed out that the following day they would likely be just as dirty and worn-out as before.

However, I am digressing. In addition, there are other elements worth noting such as cars, boats, and the rain. I am able to perceive the sound of the streetcar and the laughter of children, and I am thoroughly enjoying this moment. Our thoughts remain steadfast, just like our own selves.

They are constantly shifting topics, like a carousel, transitioning from discussing Jews to food, and then from food to politics. By the way, speaking of Jews, I caught a glimpse of two individuals yesterday while peering through the curtains. It was as if I were beholding one of the magnificent Seven Wonders of the World.

I experienced a peculiar sensation, as if I had betrayed them to the authorities and was now surreptitiously observing their unfortunate situation. 
On the opposite side, there is a residence on a boat where the captain resides with his spouse and kids.

He owns a small dog that barks incessantly. The only way we can identify the dog is by its bark and its tail, which becomes visible when it dashes around the deck. Unfortunately, it has begun to rain, causing most people to seek shelter under their umbrellas.

I am surrounded by raincoats, occasionally catching a glimpse of the back of someone's head covered in a stocking cap. In truth, I don't even have to look anymore. I can instantly recognize the women: they have become overweight from consuming potatoes, wearing either a red or green coat paired with worn-out shoes. They carry shopping bags hanging from their arms, their expressions ranging from somber to cheerful, depending on their husbands' moods.

Dear Kitty,

We were overjoyed in the Annex when we heard the news that we will be given an additional quarter pound of butter for Christmas. The newspaper stated that everyone is entitled to half a pound, but that only applies to those fortunate individuals who receive their ration books from the government. Unfortunately, as Jews in hiding, we can only afford to purchase four ration books on the black market instead of eight. Nevertheless, each of us plans to use the butter to bake something special.

Best regards,
Anne

Earlier today, I prepared two cakes and a batch of cookies. The upper floor of the house is bustling with activity, and my mother has instructed me not to engage in any studying or reading until all the household chores are completed.

Van Daan is currently in bed, taking care of her bruised rib. Throughout the day, she consistently complains, constantly requesting that the bandages be altered, and generally expressing dissatisfaction with everything. I will be relieved when she recovers and is able to take care of her own responsibilities because, I must confess, she is exceptionally diligent and tidy. As long as she is in good health, both physically and mentally, she remains quite cheerful.

Despite already hearing "shh, shh" throughout the day due to my perceived noise level, my roommate has decided to extend it to the night as well, insisting that I shouldn't even move. I am determined to ignore his requests, and if he shushes me again, I will shush him in return.

As the days pass, he becomes increasingly exasperating and egotistical. Despite his generous promises, I have not received a single cookie from him, except during the first week. Sundays are especially infuriating as he abruptly turns on the light at the crack of dawn to exercise for a mere ten minutes.

The torment feels like it lasts for hours as the chairs I use to extend my bed keep getting shaken under my tired head. After completing his warm-up exercises with some energetic arm movements, His Lordship starts getting dressed. His underwear is hanging on a hook, so he first walks over to retrieve it and then walks back, passing by my bed.

However, his tie remains on the table, prompting him to once again push and jostle his way past the chairs. Yet, I should refrain from further wasting your time by complaining about repulsive elderly individuals. It won't have any positive impact on the situation.

Unfortunately, I have had to abandon my plans for revenge, which included unscrewing the lightbulb, locking the door, and hiding his clothes, in order to prioritize peace. It seems like I'm becoming more sensible! It is important for us to approach everything we do here in a reasonable manner: studying, listening, refraining from speaking out of turn, assisting others, showing kindness, and being willing to make compromises. I can't even list all the things we need to consider!

I am concerned that my already limited common sense will be depleted too quickly, leaving me with none by the end of the war. 
Yours sincerely, Anne 
Wednesday, January 13, 1943 
Dear Kitty, 
This morning I was constantly interrupted, preventing me from completing any of the tasks I started. 
We have a new activity, which involves packing powdered gravy into packages.

Gies & Co. produces the gravy as one of their products. Mr. Kugler has been unable to find any other individuals to fill the packages, and in addition, it is more cost-effective for us to perform the task.
The prison environment is extremely dull and causes us to feel lightheaded and restless. There are distressing events occurring beyond the prison walls. Please rephrase this text.

Helpless individuals are forcibly removed from their homes, day or night, without any regard for time. They are only permitted to bring a knapsack and a small amount of money, but even these meager possessions are stolen from them during the journey. Families are cruelly separated, with men, women, and children torn apart from one another.

Upon returning home from school, children discover the unsettling absence of their parents. Similarly, women returning from shopping are confronted with the distressing sight of their homes being sealed shut, and their families mysteriously gone. Adding to the climate of fear, Christian individuals residing in Holland are deeply concerned as their beloved sons are being forcibly sent to Germany.

Fear is pervasive among everyone. Each night, numerous planes fly over Holland en route to German cities, unleashing their bombs on German soil. Countless lives are lost every hour in both Russia and Africa.

No individual can avoid being involved in the conflict as the entire globe is engulfed in war. Despite the Allies experiencing some success, there is no clear end in sight. In comparison, we are incredibly fortunate, much more so than millions of others.

In this peaceful and secure place, we prioritize using our money for purchasing food. We acknowledge our selfishness as we discuss plans for the future, such as new clothes and shoes, instead of focusing on saving every penny to assist others once the war ends and salvaging whatever resources we can. Meanwhile, the children in our community roam around wearing thin shirts and wooden shoes.

Walking through the chilly streets with no coats, caps, stockings, or anyone to assist them, these individuals find solace in nibbling on a carrot to ease their hunger. Despite the freezing temperatures, they make their way from their frigid homes to an even colder classroom. The situation in Holland has deteriorated to the point where groups of children approach strangers on the streets, desperately pleading for a morsel of bread.

Although I could spend hours recounting the immense suffering caused by the war, it would only serve to deepen my own misery. Our only option is to patiently await the war's conclusion as calmly as we can. Both Jews and Christians, as well as the entire world, find themselves in a state of anticipation, with many unfortunately awaiting death.

Dear Kitty,

I am filled with anger, but I must hide it. I have the urge to yell, stomp my foot, shake Mother, cry, and express my frustration because of the hurtful words. 

Yours,
Anne

Every day, I endure the mocking looks and relentless accusations that she hurls at me. They pierce through me like arrows from a tightly strung bow, lodging themselves deep within my body. It feels nearly impossible to remove them. The constant torment pushes me to the brink, making me yearn for a moment of respite. I want to scream at Mother, Margot, the van Daans, Dussel, and even Father, pleading for them to leave me alone. I long for just one night where I can escape the tears that stream down my face, leaving my eyes burning and my head pounding. I yearn to be free from it all, to escape this world that suffocates me. However, I am trapped
I must hide my doubts and the pain they have caused me, as I fear their sympathy or mocking humor. Their reactions would only intensify my desire to scream.

People perceive me as a show-off when I speak, ridiculous when I am quiet, insolent when I respond, cunning when I have a good idea, lazy when I am tired, selfish when I eat slightly more than I should, and stupid, cowardly, calculating, and so on. Throughout the day, all I hear is how frustrating of a child I am, and although I try to brush it off and pretend not to be bothered, it does bother me. I wish I could request from God a different personality, one that doesn't provoke everyone.

However, this seems to be an impossible situation. I am unable to change the character I was born with, yet I am confident that I am not a malicious individual. I exert great effort in attempting to satisfy everyone, even more than they could possibly fathom.

When I'm on the upper floor, I make an effort to conceal my troubles by laughing them off, as I don't want anyone to see them. On multiple occasions, following a string of unreasonable criticisms, I have reacted sharply to my mother, saying, "I don't care about your words. Maybe you should just give up on me because I am beyond help." Naturally, she would reprimand me for talking back and proceed to virtually ignore me for a duration of two days.

Then, out of nowhere, she would completely forget and treat me like she treats everyone else. It is not possible for me to go from being happy one day to being angry the next. I prefer to choose a middle ground, which is not exactly perfect, and keep my thoughts to myself.

Maybe one day I will show the others the same disdain they show me. How I wish I could. 
Sincerely, Anne 
Friday, February 5, 1943 
My dear Kitty, 
Although it has been a long time since I last wrote to you about these conflicts, nothing has changed.
At first, Mr. Dussel regarded our conflicts as significant and made efforts to resolve them. However, over time, he has become accustomed to them and no longer attempts to intervene.

Margot and Peter can't be described as "young" by any means; they are both incredibly quiet and dull. Comparatively, I stand out significantly, and I constantly hear people saying, "Why can't you be more like Margot and Peter? They don't behave like that." I despise it.

I must admit that I have no inclination whatsoever to emulate Margot. Her lack of determination and passivity do not align with my preferences; she easily succumbs to the influence of others and consistently retreats when faced with pressure. I aspire to possess more boldness and assertiveness!
However, I choose to keep ideas like these to myself as I fear that if I were to present them as a defense, others would simply laugh at me. The atmosphere during meals is often charged with tension.

Thankfully, the outbursts are occasionally subdued by the presence of the "soup eaters," the colleagues who visit the office kitchen to enjoy a cup of soup for lunch. 
During the afternoon, Mr. van Daan once again mentioned how little Mar gets to eat.

"And you know," she kept talking, "my father once advised me that if a man ever became disrespectful, I should remind him, 'Remember, sir, that I am a lady,' and he would understand my message." We burst into laughter, as if she had just shared a funny joke with us.
Even Peter, despite his usual quietness, sometimes brings about laughter. He has the unfortunate habit of loving foreign words without understanding their meanings.

During one afternoon, we were unable to access the restroom due to visitors in the office. Faced with an urgent need, an individual went to the bathroom but neglected to flush the toilet. To alert us about the unpleasant odor, they affixed a sign to the bathroom door that read: "RSVP - gas!" Naturally, their intention was to convey "Danger - gas!" but they believed "RSVP" appeared more refined.

He was completely unaware that it meant "please reply."

WEDNESDAY, MARCH 10, 1943 
My dearest Kitty, 
Last night, we experienced a power outage, and on top of that, the sounds of gunfire continued relentlessly until dawn.
I continue to struggle with my fear of flying and gunshots, often feeling the need to retreat and hide.

Almost every night, I find comfort in sleeping in my father's bed. It may sound juvenile, but you won't understand until it happens to you! The loud noise from the ack-ack guns is so overwhelming that you can't even hear your own voice.

Mrs. Beaverbrook, a believer in fate, almost couldn't hold back her tears and whispered timidly, "Oh, it's absolutely dreadful. The sound of the guns is just overwhelming!" - which essentially means "I am extremely frightened."
The situation appeared less severe when illuminated by candlelight compared to the darkness.

I trembled, as if I had a high temperature, and pleaded with Father to ignite the candle once more. However, he remained stubborn, insisting that no light should be present. Unexpectedly, a volley of machine-gun fire erupted, a sound far more distressing than the noise of antiaircraft guns.

Mother quickly got out of bed and, much to Pim's irritation, lit the candle. When he complained, she firmly replied, "Remember, Anne is not a former soldier!" And that settled the matter.

I don't believe van D. has any other fears. To update you on the latest happenings in the Secret Annex, I should also mention this. Can you please rephrase this text?

He made sure not to go up to the loft at night. A couple of evenings ago (when it was still light at seven-thirty), Peter went up to the loft to retrieve some old newspapers. In order to descend the ladder, he had to grip the trapdoor firmly.

Without glancing, he set his hand down and was startled and pained to the point of almost losing his balance on the ladder. After being bitten by a rat and having his pajamas soaked in blood, it was no wonder that he was shaken. Petting a rat is far from enjoyable, especially when it takes a chunk out of your arm.

Friday, March 12, 1943

THURSDAY, MARCH 18, 1943 
Dear Kitty, 
Turkey has joined the war.
I was filled with great excitement, eagerly anticipating the radio reports. However, my anticipation quickly turned to disappointment within a short span of time.

Turkey has not yet joined the war. A member of the cabinet merely mentioned the possibility of Turkey abandoning its neutrality in the near future. In Dam Square, a newspaper vendor was loudly proclaiming "Turkey supports England!" as people eagerly grabbed the newspapers from him.

We received the encouraging rumor in this manner. The news was that thousand-guilder notes would no longer be considered valid. In order to exchange a thousand-guilder bill, you must provide an explanation of how you obtained it and provide supporting evidence. These bills can still be used for tax payments, but only until the following week. The five-hundred notes will also expire at the same deadline.

Gies & Co. had some remaining thousand-guilder bills that were not yet accounted for, and they decided to use them to pay their estimated taxes for future years. This indicates that everything is legitimate.

It was evident that the wounded individuals took pride in their injuries, as if having more wounds made them more honorable.
