I accidentally dropped Dussel's soap on the floor and unintentionally stepped on it, resulting in a missing piece. I have already approached Father to make amends for the damage caused, particularly considering that Dussel receives only one bar of subpar wartime soap per month.

On Thursday, March 25, 1943, I, Anne, wrote a letter to my dear friend Kitty. In the letter, I recounted an incident that occurred the previous night. My mother, father, Margot, and I were all sitting together when Peter suddenly entered the room and whispered something to my father. I overheard words like "a barrel falling over in the warehouse" and "someone fiddling with the door." This news made me extremely anxious and I turned pale. Margot tried to calm me down while we waited for my father and Peter to return.
After a brief moment, Mrs. van Daan ascended from downstairs where she had been listening to the radio. She informed us that Pim had requested her to switch it off and quietly go upstairs.

However, when attempting to be quiet, the old stairs seemed to creak even louder. After five minutes, Peter and Pim returned, their faces pale, to share what they had experienced. They had positioned themselves beneath the staircase and patiently waited.

There was no activity. 
Suddenly, they were startled by the sound of two doors being forcefully closed within the house. Pim quickly rushed up the stairs, while Peter went to alert Dussel. Eventually, Dussel appeared upstairs, although he was not pleased and caused a commotion.
Next, we quietly made our way in our stocking-covered feet to the van Daans' apartment on the floor above. We were careful not to make any noise.
Mr. van D. had fallen ill with a severe cold and had already retired to bed. In hushed tones, we gathered around his bedside and quietly shared our suspicions with one another.
Mrs. van D. and I were startled when someone coughed loudly, nearly causing us to have a nervous fit.
He continued coughing until someone suggested giving him codeine, which promptly relieved his cough. We waited and waited again, but there was no sound.

After careful consideration, we concluded that the burglars fled in a hurry upon hearing footsteps in the normally silent building. However, a new issue arose as the chairs in the private office were arranged neatly around the radio, which was playing an English station. If the burglars had forcefully entered the premises and the air-raid wardens noticed it and contacted the police, there could be severe consequences.

Mr. van Daan arose, donned his coat and pants, and wore his hat as he cautiously accompanied Father down the stairs. Peter, equipped with a hefty hammer for precaution, followed closely behind. Meanwhile, the ladies, including Margot and myself, anxiously awaited as the men returned after five minutes, assuring us that there was no indication of any movement within the premises.

We had decided against using any water or flushing the toilet, but with everyone feeling uneasy and having upset stomachs, the bathroom became quite unpleasant after each of us had a turn. These kinds of situations are often accompanied by additional mishaps, and this one was no different. Firstly, the Westertoren bells, which I had always found comforting, ceased their chiming.

Mr. Voskuijl departed early last night, and we were uncertain whether he had entrusted Bep with the key and if she had neglected to secure the door. However, this matter held little significance at present.

As the night had only just begun, we found ourselves uncertain about what lay ahead. However, we were slightly relieved by the fact that there had been no noise between eight-fifteen, when the intruder had initially entered the building and put our lives at risk, and ten-thirty. Upon further consideration, it seemed increasingly unlikely that a burglar would have chosen to break in so early in the evening.

When there were still individuals on the streets, it crossed our minds that the warehouse manager at the neighboring Keg Company might still be working. Due to the commotion and the lack of soundproofing, it is simple to misinterpret the noises.
Additionally, moments of danger can often cause your imagination to deceive you. Consequently, we retired to bed, although sleep eluded us. Father, Mother, and Mr. [last name] were present.

Dussel and I were awake for most of the night, and I'm not exaggerating when I say that I barely slept at all. This morning, the men went downstairs to check if the outside door was still locked, but everything was fine! Naturally, we shared all the details of the incident with the entire office staff, even though it had been quite unpleasant.

After these kinds of things have happened, it becomes much easier to laugh at them, and Bep was the only person who took us seriously. 
Sincerely, Anne 
PS. This morning, the toilet got clogged, and Father had to use a long wooden pole to remove a large amount of waste and strawberry recipes (which we currently use as toilet paper). 
Can you please rephrase this text?

Later on, we set fire to the pole. 
Dear Kitty,
Our shorthand course is completed, and now we are focusing on enhancing our speed.
Aren't we clever!

I would like to share more about my "time killers," a term I use to describe my courses because they mainly serve to pass the time and bring me closer to the end of my time at this place. Personally, I have a strong passion for mythology, particularly Greek and Roman gods. Unfortunately, everyone around here believes that my interest is merely a temporary fascination, as they have never encountered a teenager with an appreciation for mythology.

It seems that I am the first one here!
Mr. van Daan is currently suffering from a cold.

Instead, he has a mildly irritated throat, but he is exaggerating the situation. He goes to great lengths to find relief, such as gargling with camomile tea, applying a myrrh tincture to the roof of his mouth, and generously applying Mentholatum to his chest, nose, gums, and tongue. Additionally, his mood is extremely unpleasant.

Rauter, a prominent figure in Germany, delivered a speech where he stated that all individuals of Jewish heritage must vacate the territories under German occupation by July 1st. He expressed that the province of Utrecht will undergo a process of removing Jews, comparing it to the elimination of cockroaches, from April 1st to May 1st. Similarly, the provinces of North and South Holland will go through this process between May 1st and June 1st. It is disheartening to witness the suffering inflicted upon these individuals.

Sent away to unclean slaughterhouses, resembling a group of diseased and forsaken cattle. However, I shall refrain from further discussion on this matter, as my own contemplations provoke distressing dreams.

There is a positive development to report, as the Labor Exchange and the County Clerk's Office both experienced incidents of sabotage. In separate events, unidentified individuals, pretending to be German police, successfully subdued the guards and staff, resulting in the destruction of significant documents.

Dear Kitty,

I hope you're not in the mood for pranks today, considering the date. Unfortunately, I have some unfortunate news to share. Mr. Kleiman, our cheerful companion, experienced another episode of gastrointestinal hemorrhaging yesterday and will need to remain in bed for at least three weeks.

I need to inform you that he has been experiencing frequent stomach troubles, which unfortunately cannot be cured. Additionally, Bep is currently suffering from the flu. Lastly, Mr.  could you please provide further information or complete the sentence.

Next week, Voskuijl has a scheduled hospital visit, as it is likely that he has an ulcer and will require surgical intervention. Additionally, the managers of Pomosin Industries arrived from Frankfurt to engage in discussions regarding the upcoming Op ekta deliveries.
Father had discussed the important points with Mr. Kleiman, but there was not sufficient time to provide Mr. Kugler with a comprehensive briefing.

The men had just arrived from Frankfurt, and Father was already filled with anxiety about how the discussions would unfold. He wished he could be present, longing to be downstairs in the midst of it all. 
"Perhaps if I lie down and press my ear against the floor," he suggested.

The private office will be where they are taken, and you will have the ability to hear everything. Father's expression became more relaxed, and yesterday morning at ten-thirty, Margot and Pim (two sets of ears are better than one) positioned themselves on the floor. By noon, the conversations were not yet concluded, but Father was not able to continue eavesdropping. He was suffering greatly from having to lie in such an unusual and uncomfortable position for hours.

At two-thirty, voices were heard in the hall, and I assumed his position while Margot stayed with me. The conversation was excessively lengthy and uninteresting, causing me to unexpectedly doze off on the chilly, unwelcoming linoleum floor. Margot refrained from touching me out of fear that they would overhear us, and naturally, she couldn't raise her voice.
After a restful half hour of sleep, I suddenly woke up with a jolt.

Fortunately, Margot had paid more attention during the important discussion, as I had completely forgotten every word of it. It was lucky for me that she was able to recall the details. 
Best wishes, 
Anne 
Friday, April 2, 1943 
Dear Kitty, 
I must confess another wrongdoing that I have committed. Please allow me to rephrase my previous statement.

Last night, as I lay in bed, anticipating Father's arrival to tuck me in and say my prayers, Mother entered the room. She sat on my bed and softly asked, "Anne, Daddy is not ready. Would you like me to listen to your prayers tonight?" 
"No, Momsy," I answered. 
Mother stood up, lingered by my bedside for a moment, and then proceeded to slowly make her way towards the door.

In an instant, she abruptly turned, her face contorting with anguish, and uttered, "I don't wish to harbor resentment towards you. I am unable to force you to love me!" A couple of tears trickled down her cheeks as she departed through the doorway. 
I remained motionless, contemplating how unkind it was for me to reject her so mercilessly, yet I also acknowledged that I lacked the ability to respond to her in any other manner.

I cannot act hypocritically and join in prayer with her when I am not genuinely inclined to do so. It simply does not function in that manner. I experienced sympathy for Mother - a deep sense of sorrow - because for the first time in my existence, I realized she was affected by my lack of warmth.

When she expressed her inability to make me love her, I noticed the sadness reflected in her face. It is difficult to be honest, but the reality is that she is the one who has rejected me. Her lack of tact and hurtful jokes, which I do not find amusing, have made me immune to any displays of affection from her.

Every time I hear her harsh words, my heart sinks, and in the same way, her heart sank when she realized our love was gone. She spent half the night crying, unable to sleep. My father avoids looking at me, and if our eyes happen to meet, I can sense his unspoken words: "Why are you so unkind?"

"I cannot apologize for making my mother sad, as I simply told the truth and she was bound to find out eventually. I appear indifferent to her tears and my father's disapproving glances, because they are now experiencing the emotions I have always felt. I only feel sorry for my mother, as she will have to determine her own response to this situation."

I choose to maintain my silence and distance myself from others, and I have no intention of avoiding the truth. I believe that the longer we postpone sharing the truth, the more difficult it will be for them to accept it when they eventually hear it. 
With love, Anne 
TUESDAY, APRIL 27, 1943 
Dear Kitty, 
The atmosphere in the house is still tense after the recent arguments. Everyone is angry with each other: my mother and I, Mr.
Van Daan, Father, Mother, and Mrs. van D. create a fantastic atmosphere, wouldn't you agree?

Anne's usual list of shortcomings has once again been thoroughly discussed.
Our German guests returned last Saturday and stayed until six o'clock.

All of us remained upstairs, too afraid to make even the slightest movement. With no one else present in the building or nearby neighborhood, the sound of each footstep in the private office could be heard. Once again, I am feeling restless and fidgety from being forced to sit motionless for such a long time.
Mr. Voskuijl is currently in the hospital, while Mr. Kleiman has returned to the office.

His stomach ceased bleeding earlier than its usual timeframe. He informed us that the County Clerk's Office endured additional damage as the firemen inadvertently flooded the entire building instead of solely extinguishing the fire. This news brings me joy!

The destruction of the Carlton Hotel occurred when two British planes carrying firebombs landed directly on the German Officers' Club. A massive fire erupted, engulfing the entire intersection of Vijzelstraat and Singel.

The frequency of air strikes on German cities is rising on a daily basis. It has been quite a while since we had a decent night's sleep, and I have noticeable fatigue under my eyes due to lack of rest. Furthermore, our meals are of poor quality.

Breakfast consists of bread without butter and substitute coffee. Lunch for the past two weeks has been either spinach or cooked lettuce served with large potatoes that have a spoiled and slightly sweet flavor.

If you're on a diet, the Annex is the ideal location! Although those upstairs grumble, we don't perceive it as such a terrible situation. All the Dutch men who were involved in the 1940 conflict, whether they fought or were enlisted, have been summoned to serve in prisoner-of-war facilities.
I believe they are implementing this precautionary measure due to the invasion. Can you please rephrase this text?

Dear Kitty,

Yesterday was Dussel's birthday. Initially, he seemed uninterested in celebrating it. However, when Miep arrived with a generously filled shopping bag containing numerous gifts, he became as thrilled as a young child. His beloved "Lotje" had sent him a variety of treats such as eggs, butter, cookies, lemonade, bread, cognac, spice cake, flowers, oranges, chocolate, books, and writing paper.

Sincerely, 
Anne
He stacked his gifts on a table and exhibited them for a minimum of three days, the foolish old man! You shouldn't assume that he is hungry. We discovered bread, cheese, jam, and eggs in his pantry.

It is truly shameful that Dussel, whom we have treated kindly and sheltered to protect from harm, would selfishly keep things hidden from us. We have always been generous in sharing what we have with him! But even more disappointing is his unwillingness to reciprocate this generosity towards Mr.
Kleiman, Mr. Voskuijl, and Bep receive nothing from him.

According to Dussel, the oranges that Kleiman desperately needs for his stomach will have an even greater positive effect on Dussel's own stomach. The constant sound of gunshots tonight has forced me to gather my belongings and prepare to flee four times already. In anticipation of having to leave, I packed a suitcase with essential items, but my mother rightly questioned, "Where would you go?" The entire country of Holland is facing consequences for the workers' strikes.

A state of martial law has been announced, and individuals will receive one fewer coupon for butter. Those children are misbehaving. Tonight, I took on the challenging job of washing Mother's hair, which is quite difficult in the present times. Can you please paraphrase this passage?

Due to the lack of shampoo, we are forced to utilize a highly adhesive liquid cleanser. Additionally, combing our hair has become challenging for Mom as the family comb is now left with only ten teeth. Comparatively, when reflecting upon our existence here, I often realize that we are living in a paradise in comparison to the Jews who are not in hiding.

After everything has returned to its usual state, I will likely ponder how we, who have always enjoyed such comfortable conditions, could have stooped so low in terms of manners. Specifically, I am referring to the fact that the dining table has been covered with the same oilcloth since our arrival.

After extensive use, it is far from being spotless. I make an effort to clean it, but the dishcloth was bought before we went into hiding and it now has more holes than actual cloth, making the task of cleaning it quite pointless. Throughout the winter, the van Daans have been sleeping on the same flannel sheet, which cannot be washed due to the limited supply and rationing of detergent.

Additionally, the item is of extremely low quality, rendering it practically ineffective. Father is seen wearing worn-out trousers and a tie that is also showing signs of deterioration. Mama's corset broke today and cannot be fixed, while Margot is wearing a bra that is two sizes too small. Both Mother and Margot have been sharing the same three undershorts all winter, and mine are so tiny that they don't even cover my stomach.

I often ponder how we, with our worn and aged possessions, can aspire to reclaim the position we held before the war. It seems challenging to overcome these obstacles. The Annex residents' perspective on the war is something worth considering.

According to all of us, this esteemed individual possesses remarkable understanding of politics. However, he foresees that we will need to remain in this place until the conclusion of '43. Although it is a lengthy duration, it is still conceivable to endure until that time.

Who can guarantee us that this war, which has only brought us pain and sadness, will eventually come to an end? And that neither us nor our allies will have suffered any harm long before that happens? Nobody can assure us of this.

This is why tension fills each day, as expectation, hope, and fear all contribute to it. For instance, we feel tense when we hear a noise within or outside our home, when guns are fired, or when we read new declarations in the newspaper, as we fear that our helpers may have to hide at some point. Nowadays, conversations about the need for hiding are prevalent.

We are uncertain about the exact number of individuals currently in hiding. While the number is relatively small compared to the overall population, we will likely be amazed in the future by the significant number of kind-hearted individuals in Holland who were willing to offer shelter to Jews and Christians, regardless of their financial situation. Additionally, there is a staggering amount of people possessing counterfeit identification documents. Mrs.

Van Daan had a sudden suggestion when she learned that obtaining false IDs had become easier. She suggested that all of us get one without hesitation, as if it was a simple task, completely disregarding the concerns of Father and Mr.
The Van Daan family seemed to be very wealthy. Mrs. Van Daan frequently made ridiculous statements, and her son, Putti, also often joined in.

Filled with frustration, which is to be expected, Kerli declares, "Once everything is finished, I plan on getting baptized." Shortly after, she exclaims, "For as long as I can recall, my heart has yearned to visit Jerusalem. I feel a sense of belonging only among fellow Jews!" Pim, on the other hand, maintains an optimistic outlook, supported by his rationality.
Mr. Dussel improvises everything, and anyone who wants to challenge him should reconsider. In Alfred Dussel's house, his authority is unquestioned, but Anne Frank strongly disagrees with this.

The opinions of the other members of the Annex family regarding the war are not important. Only these four individuals hold significance when it comes to politics. In reality, only two of them truly have influence, but Madame van Daan and Dussel also consider themselves as significant. Please rephrase this passage.

My dearest Kit, 
I have just witnessed a intense aerial battle between German and English pilots. Sadly, due to their aircraft being engulfed in flames, a few Allied airmen were forced to parachute to safety. Interestingly, our milkman, who resides in Halfweg, came across a group of four Canadians sitting by the roadside, and it turns out that one of them was fluent in Dutch.

He inquired the milkman if he possessed a lighter for his cigarette, and proceeded to inform him that the team had comprised of six individuals. The pilot had tragically perished in the fire, and the fifth crew member had managed to conceal himself in an undisclosed location. The German Security Police arrived to apprehend the four remaining men, all of whom had miraculously escaped unharmed.

How is it possible for someone to remain calm and composed after jumping out of a burning airplane? Despite the intense heat, we are required to start a fire every other day in order to dispose of our vegetable peels and garbage. We are prohibited from throwing anything into trash cans as it may be visible to warehouse employees.

A single moment of carelessness could spell disaster for us! All college students are being requested to sign an official declaration stating that they "feel empathy towards the Germans and endorse the New Order." The majority, eighty percent, have chosen to follow their moral compass, despite the harsh consequences. Any student who declines to sign will be relocated to a German labor camp.

What will happen to the young people in our country if they are all required to engage in demanding work in Germany? Last evening, the sound of gunfire was so loud that my mother closed the window. I was in Pim's bed at the time. Suddenly, directly above us, we heard Mrs. [last name]...
V suddenly jumped up, as though she had been bitten by Mouschi. Immediately after, there was a loud boom that sounded like...
I screamed, "Lights! Lights!" as a firebomb landed beside my bed.
After Pim turned on the lamp, I anticipated the room would suddenly catch fire. However, there were no flames to be seen.
Mr. and Mrs., we all hurriedly went upstairs to find out what was happening.
D. noticed a red glow coming from the open window, leading him to believe that there was a fire close by. On the other hand, she was confident that our house was on fire. Mrs.
Van D. stood beside her bed, her knees knocking, when the boom came. Dus sel remained upstairs to smoke a cigarette while we crawled back into bed.
The shooting resumed less than fifteen minutes later, as Mrs. van D.

I quickly got out of bed and went downstairs to Dussel's room, seeking the comfort that I couldn't find with my spouse. Dussel greeted me warmly, saying "Come into my bed, my dear!" This caused us to burst into laughter, and the sound of the guns no longer bothered us; all our fears had disappeared. 
With love, Anne 

Sunday, June 13, 1943 
Dear Kitty, 
The poem my father wrote for my birthday is too good not to share.

Margot has done an excellent job translating Pim's German verses into Dutch. Let's take a look at her impressive work. The poem starts with a familiar overview of the year's events and goes on to say:

Being the youngest among us, though not so little anymore,
Your life may present challenges, as we have the task
Of assuming the role of your teachers, which can be quite a bore.

Please provide an alternative phrasing for this text.

"We have ample experience! Trust me!" 
"We have successfully accomplished this in the past, you understand. 
We are familiar with the procedures, we have the same knowledge." 
For countless ages, consistently unchanged.

It is easy to overlook our own flaws and dismiss them as insignificant, while we tend to magnify and criticize the shortcomings of others. We often find fault easily when it is someone else's problem, but it can be challenging for our parents, despite their efforts, to treat us with fairness and kindness. Criticizing and finding fault has become a habit that is difficult to let go of. When you live with older individuals, all you can do is try your best to understand and empathize with their perspective.

Enduring their constant nagging is difficult, yet undeniable. Swallowing the bitter pill is necessary, as it serves to maintain harmony. The lengthy period spent here has not been without purpose, as wasting time goes against your intellect.

You spend most of your day reading and studying,
Determined to escape from boredom's sting.
But the question that's tougher to handle and share,
Is "What should I wear? I'm in need of new underwear.
My clothes are too snug, my shirt is a mere strip,
I feel so uncomfortable, like a fashion misfit!

In order to wear my shoes, I have to lift my toes,
Oh dear, I'm burdened with so many troubles and woes!"
Margot had difficulty finding a rhyming word for "food," so I'm omitting it. But,
apart from that, don't you agree that it's a wonderful poem?
As for everything else, I've been incredibly fortunate and have received several delightful gifts, such as a large book on the topic I adore the most, Greek and Roman mythology.

I have no reason to complain about the shortage of candy either; everyone had used up their remaining supplies. Being the youngest in the Annex, I received more than I deserved. 
With love, 
Anne 
Tuesday, June 15, 1943 
Dear Kitty, 
Many things have happened, but I worry that I'm boring you with my dull conversations and that you would prefer fewer letters.
I'll summarize the news for you: Contrary to expectations, Mr. Voskuijl did not undergo surgery for his ulcer.

After the doctors placed him on the operating table and performed the surgery, they discovered that he had cancer. However, the cancer had progressed to such an advanced stage that an operation would have been ineffective. Consequently, they closed the incision, kept him hospitalized for a duration of three weeks, ensured he received proper nutrition, and subsequently discharged him to return home.

However, they committed an unforgivable mistake by informing the destitute man about his grim future. As a result, he is now unable to continue working and spends his days at home, surrounded by his eight children, brooding over his impending death. I deeply sympathize with him and regret not being able to leave the house. If circumstances allowed, I would visit him frequently and provide support to distract him from his worries.

Unfortunately, the absence of the good man has left us without information about the activities and conversations taking place in the warehouse, which is a significant setback for us. Mr. Voskuijl was our most valuable informant.

We are in need of assistance and guidance regarding safety precautions. We are deeply saddened by his absence. It will be our responsibility to surrender our radio to the authorities next month. Kindly rephrase this passage.

Mr. Kleiman possesses a small concealed set in his residence which he is providing us as a substitute for our splendid cabinet radio. It is regrettable that we must relinquish our sizable Philips radio, but when one is in hiding, it is imperative to avoid attracting attention from the authorities.

Certainly, we will place the "baby" radio upstairs. When there are already hidden Jews and hidden money, what is a clandestine radio? All over the country, people are trying to find an old radio that they can hand over instead of their "morale booster." It is true: as the reports from outside become increasingly worse, the radio, with its amazing voice, helps us stay hopeful and reminds us to stay positive, saying to ourselves, "Stay cheerful, keep your spirits up, things are bound to improve!" 
Yours, Anne 
SUNDAY, JULY 11, 1943 
Dear Kitty, 
Returning to the topic of raising children (once again), let me inform you that I am doing my best

Behaving like a model child is difficult when you have to interact with people you dislike, especially when you don't genuinely agree with them. However, I've noticed that being a bit hypocritical helps me navigate these situations better than my usual approach of speaking my mind (even though nobody ever solicits my opinion or cares about it). Although I occasionally forget my role and struggle to control my anger when they're being unfair, this leads to others labeling me as the most impertinent girl in the world for the following month.

Do you not think that I am deserving of pity at times? Fortunately, I am not prone to being grumpy, as that could lead to me becoming bitter and ill-tempered. I often find the funny aspects in being scolded, although it is easier when someone else is the target of criticism.

Additionally, after extensive contemplation, I have made the decision to stop using shorthand. The primary reasons for this are to allocate more time to my other subjects and also due to the unfortunate condition of my eyes. It is a rather sorrowful tale.

I have developed severe nearsightedness and it seems like I should have gotten glasses a long time ago. (Oh no, I'm worried about looking foolish!). However, as you are aware, individuals in hiding cannot easily do so. 
Could you please rephrase this text?
Yesterday, the topic of conversation among everyone here was Anne's eyes due to Mother's suggestion that I accompany Mrs. to the ophthalmologist.
My knees feel weak, as it's not a minor issue. Venturing outside! Imagine, strolling along the road!

Initially, I couldn't fathom it. I was filled with fear, but then I felt relieved. However, it is not as straightforward as it seems; the different governing bodies responsible for authorizing such a measure encountered difficulties in promptly reaching a conclusion.

Before setting off, they had to thoroughly assess all the challenges and potential dangers, even though Miep was eager to depart right away with me by her side. In the interim, I retrieved my gray coat from the wardrobe, but it appeared so petite that it could have belonged to my younger sibling. We adjusted the length, yet I still struggled to fasten it.

I am extremely curious about their decision, but I doubt they will be able to come up with a plan because the British have arrived in Sicily and Father is expecting a swift resolution. Bep has assigned Margot and me a lot of administrative tasks, which makes us feel significant and greatly assists her. While anyone can handle filing letters and making entries in a sales book, we perform these tasks with exceptional precision.

Miep appears to be carrying an excessive amount of items, resembling a pack mule. Almost every day, she ventures out to gather vegetables and returns on her bicycle with her large shopping bags filled with purchases. Additionally, she is the one who brings five library books with her every Saturday.

Saturdays are eagerly anticipated by us because they bring the joy of books. We resemble excited children receiving a gift. Most people are unaware of the immense value that books hold for someone confined indoors.

We have limited forms of entertainment, such as reading, studying, and listening to the radio. 
From Anne, 
Tuesday, July 13, 1943 
The table I love 
Yesterday, my father granted me the opportunity to politely ask Mr. Dus sel if I could use the table in our room for two afternoons a week, specifically from four to five-thirty. 
Please provide an alternative phrasing for this passage.

I am currently present there daily from two-thirty to four o'clock while Dussel takes a nap. However, for the remainder of the day, I am not allowed to enter the room or use the table. It is not feasible for me to study in the adjacent room during the afternoon due to the excessive activity. Additionally, Father occasionally prefers to occupy the desk during that time.

After considering it as a reasonable favor, I politely approached Dussel and asked. Can you guess what the response from the knowledgeable gentleman was? It was a simple, straightforward "No." I felt furious and refused to allow myself to be dismissed so easily.

Despite my efforts to find out the reason behind his refusal, I was unsuccessful. Essentially, his response conveyed that he also needed to dedicate time to studying, and if he couldn't do so in the afternoons, he wouldn't be able to find any other suitable time. He emphasized the importance of completing the task he had assigned himself, as starting without finishing would be pointless.

In addition, it seems like you don't prioritize your studies. Why would you choose to focus on mythology? And activities like reading and knitting are not considered productive either. Can you please rephrase this text?

"I am not willing to give up using that table," I asserted. "Mr. Dussel, I am dedicated to my work and cannot study in the afternoons if I am next door. I kindly ask you to reconsider my request." After speaking these words, Anne turned her back on the offended doctor and pretended he didn't exist.

I was consumed by anger and felt that Dussel had acted incredibly impolite (which he definitely had) while I had remained very polite. Later that evening, I finally got a chance to talk to Pim and I explained what had happened. Together, we discussed what my next move should be because I had no intention of giving up and wanted to handle the situation on my own. Pim provided me with a general plan on how to approach Dussel, but advised me to wait until the next day since I was in such a state of agitation.
After finishing the dishes, I disregarded the previous advice and decided to wait for Dusse l. Pim, who was sitting nearby, provided a calming presence. I started by addressing Mr.

Despite Dussel's belief that further discussion is futile, I implore him to reconsider. Dussel responded with a charming smile, stating that he is always open to discussing the matter, even though it has already been resolved. Despite Dussel's persistent interruptions, I continued to express my thoughts. I reminded him that when he first arrived, we agreed to share the room. If we were to divide it fairly, he would have the entire morning while I would have the entire afternoon.

I don't need a lot, just two afternoons a week seems fair to me." Dussel immediately stood up abruptly, as if he had been startled. "You shouldn't be discussing your rights to the room. Where do you expect me to go?
Perhaps I should request Mr. van Daan to construct a small hiding place for me in the attic. It seems I am not the only one struggling to find a peaceful spot to focus on my work.

You are constantly seeking confrontation. If your sister Margot, who is entitled to more workspace than you, had approached me with the same request, I would have never considered denying it. However, in your case...
Once again, he mentioned the topic of mythology and knitting, and once again Anne felt offended. However, I remained composed and allowed Dussel to continue speaking.
Unfortunately, engaging in conversation with you seems to be an impossible task. Your self-centeredness is truly disgraceful, as you prioritize your own desires above everyone else's.

I have never encountered such an immature individual. However, in the end, I will reluctantly allow you to have your way. I don't want others to later claim that Anne Frank failed her exams because Mr. Dussel refused to give up his table! He continued speaking incessantly, overwhelming me with a flood of words that I struggled to follow.

Father, please be quiet. Shh, Ott.

Dear Kitty,

It is already nine o'clock and time for breakfast! Unfortunately, every time I sit down to write to you, there is usually something significant that has occurred, but it tends to be more unpleasant than pleasant. 

Best regards,

This time, however, there is something incredible happening. 
On Wednesday, September 8, as we were tuned in to the seven o'clock news, we were greeted with an announcement: "We have some truly remarkable news to share: Italy has surrendered." Italy has given up without any conditions! The broadcast from the Netherlands, coming from England, started at eight-fifteen and shared the news: "Dear listeners, just an hour and fifteen minutes ago, right after I finished writing my daily report, we received the astonishing news of Italy's surrender.

I must confess, today I felt an unprecedented joy when discarding my notes into the waste paper basket!"
The American national anthem, "God Save the King," and the Russian anthem, "The Internationale," were performed. The Dutch program, as usual, managed to be inspirational without excessive optimism. The British forces have successfully reached Naples.

The Germans have taken control of Northern Italy. The truce was agreed upon on Friday, September 3, which coincided with the British arrival in Italy. The German newspapers are filled with angry outbursts about Badoglio and the Italian king, accusing them of betrayal.
However, there is also some unfortunate news regarding Mr. Kleiman.

We all have a great fondness for him because he is always cheerful and incredibly courageous, despite constantly battling illness and experiencing pain. Unfortunately, his condition limits his ability to eat and engage in physical activities such as walking.
Recently, my mother made a statement that holds true as I enter a room and witness the radiant appearance of the sun.

Currently, it appears that he needs to be admitted to the hospital for a challenging surgery on his stomach, and he will have to remain there for a minimum of four weeks. It was quite a sight to witness his farewell, as he maintained a sense of normalcy, almost as if he were simply running an errand.

Dear Kitty,

The relationships within the Annex are deteriorating steadily. We are cautious about speaking during mealtime, as any comment is likely to provoke resentment or be misunderstood by someone.

Voskuijl visits us from time to time, but it is unfortunate that he is not in a good state. His attitude is not helping his family, as he seems to have the mindset of not caring because he believes he will die soon.

When considering how easily offended everyone is here, I can only imagine how sensitive the atmosphere must be at the Voskuijls' place. Despite taking valerian daily to combat my anxiety and depression, it doesn't prevent me from feeling even more miserable the following day. A genuine, hearty laugh would be more effective than ten drops of valerian, but we have nearly forgotten how to laugh.

I sometimes worry that my face will sag from all the sorrow, causing my mouth to permanently droop at the corners. The people around me are also struggling. We all fear the oncoming winter, which is known for bringing great terror.

Another unfortunate fact that fails to bring joy to our lives is that Mr. van Maaren, the individual employed in the warehouse, is becoming increasingly suspicious of the Annex. It is evident that anyone with intelligence would have noticed by now that Miep occasionally claims to be going to the laboratory, Bep to the file room, and Mr. [van Maaren] to a different undisclosed location.
Kleiman alleges that the Opekta supplies are false, while Mr. Kugler asserts that the Annex does not belong to this building at all, but rather to the neighboring one. We are indifferent to Mr.
Mr. van Maaren, although unreliable and excessively curious, pondered the situation. He is not easily deterred by weak justifications. On a particular day, Mr. van Maaren...

Kugler, wanting to take extra precautions, decided to put on his coat and visit the drugstore nearby at twenty past twelve. Within a short span of less than five minutes, he returned and stealthily climbed the stairs to come and visit us. However, at one-fifteen, as he attempted to leave, Bep intercepted him on the landing and cautioned him about van Maaren's presence.
In the office, Mr. Kugler suddenly changed his direction and remained with us until one-thirty.

After removing his shoes, he walked in his socks, despite feeling the cold, to the front attic. He carefully descended the stairs, taking one step at a time to prevent any creaking. It took him fifteen minutes to navigate the stairs, but he eventually reached the office safely after entering from outside. 
Meanwhile, Bep had successfully dealt with van Maaren and had come to find Mr. [name].
What would people have thought when they saw the manager outside, putting on his shoes, while Kugler from the Annex had already left and was quietly descending the stairs?

Hello, you over there, in the socks!

Apart from receiving one ration stamp each for cheese, meat, and bread, the only thing she got from us was a jar of jam. Her husband, Dussel, and the office staff gifted her with flowers and food. These are the challenging times we are currently experiencing.

My family stood anxiously at the bottom of the stairs, prepared to intervene if necessary. The constant arguing, tears, and tension have become overwhelming, causing me to cry myself to sleep at night. Thankfully, I have a brief respite when I can be alone for half an hour. Although I'm managing, my appetite has disappeared and people constantly remark on my poor appearance. I must acknowledge their efforts to take care of me by providing dextrose, cod-liver oil, brewer's yeast, and calcium.

On Sundays, my nerves tend to overpower me, causing me to feel exceptionally miserable. The ambiance becomes suffocating, slow-moving, and heavy. There is an absence of any bird songs outside, and a profoundly oppressive silence envelops the house, clinging to me as if it intends to pull me down into the darkest depths of the underworld.

During times like these, Father, Mother, and Margot hold no significance for me whatsoever. I aimlessly roam from one room to another, going up and down the stairs, feeling like a helpless songbird that has lost its ability to fly and repeatedly bangs itself against the confines of its gloomy cage. A voice from within me desperately pleads, "Release me, to a place filled with fresh air and joyful laughter!"

I no longer make an effort to respond, instead, I choose to lie down on the couch. Sleeping helps to make the silence and overwhelming fear pass by faster, and it also helps to pass the time since it cannot be killed. 
Yours sincerely, Anne 
WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 3, 1943 
Beloved Kitty, 
In order to divert our thoughts and also to enhance our knowledge, Father has requested a catalog from a distance learning institution.
Margot carefully examined the thick brochure on three separate occasions.

After not finding anything that she liked and that fit within her budget, Margot's father had an easier time being satisfied. He decided to write and request a trial lesson in "Elementary Latin." He wasted no time and quickly received the lesson. Margot eagerly started working on it and ultimately decided to take the course, even though it was expensive.

Learning Latin is too difficult for me, but I have a strong desire to acquire the skill. In order to provide me with a new educational endeavor, my father reached out to Mr. Kleiman and requested a children's Bible. This way, I can finally gain some knowledge about the New Testament.
"Will you be gifting Anne a Bible for Hanukkah?" Margot inquired, feeling a bit unsettled. "Yes, I am planning to do so."
Father suggested that St. Nicholas Day might be a more suitable occasion.

The connection between Jesus and Hanukkah is not strong. 
Due to the broken vacuum cleaner, I am forced to use an old brush on the rug each night. 
Despite the closed window, the light being on, and the stove burning, I find myself diligently brushing the rug.

"I'm certain that will be a problem," I silently pondered on the first occasion. "There will undoubtedly be complaints." My prediction proved accurate: Mother developed a headache due to the dense clouds of dust swirling throughout the room, Margot's recently acquired Latin dictionary became coated in dirt, and Rim complained that the floor appeared unchanged. I received minimal appreciation for my efforts.

Starting from now, we have made the decision to light the stove at seven-thirty on Sunday mornings instead of five-thirty. I am concerned about the potential risks involved. How will our neighbors perceive the sight of smoke coming from our chimney?
Since we initially went into hiding, the curtains have remained securely fastened to the windows. Occasionally, one of the occupants cannot resist the temptation to sneak a glimpse outside.

The outcome: an onslaught of criticism. The reaction: "Oh, nobody will realize." This is how every instance of negligence starts and concludes. Nobody will observe, nobody will listen, nobody will give any consideration whatsoever.
It may be easy to express, but can it be considered true? Currently, the intense arguments have calmed down, with only Dussel and the van Daans still in disagreement. Dussel is discussing Mrs.

Van D. consistently refers to her as "that old bat" or "that stupid hag," while Mrs. van D. reciprocates by calling our highly knowledgeable gentleman an "old maid" or a "sensitive neurotic spinster," and so on.

If you were to read all of my letters at once, you would notice that they were written in different moods. It bothers me to be so influenced by the moods in the annex, but I'm not the only one. We all experience these fluctuations. When I am deeply engrossed in a book, I need to adjust my mindset before interacting with others, as I wouldn't want them to think I am odd.

I'm currently in the midst of a depression, and it's difficult for me to pinpoint exactly what triggered it. However, I believe it stems from my constant feelings of cowardice that haunt me in every situation. Earlier tonight, while Bep was still present, the doorbell rang persistently and loudly.

I immediately paled, my stomach twisted, and my heart raced uncontrollably - all due to my fear. When I lie in bed at night, I envision myself isolated in a dungeon without my parents. Alternatively, I wander the streets or imagine the Annex engulfed in flames. Sometimes, I fear that they will come during the night to forcibly remove us, and in desperation, I find myself crawling under my bed.

I perceive everything as if it is truly happening, and the thought of it potentially occurring soon is remarkable. Miep frequently expresses her envy towards us due to the tranquility and serenity we experience in this place.

While it may be true that she is not considering our fear, I find it hard to believe that our world will ever return to normal. I often discuss the idea of "after the war," but it feels like I am merely speaking about an unrealistic fantasy that will never become a reality.

I envision the eight of us in the Annex like a small oasis of tranquility amidst a stormy sea. The secure space we currently occupy remains unscathed, but the ominous forces are steadily encroaching upon us, narrowing the gap between us and impending peril. We find ourselves ensconced in darkness and uncertainty, constantly colliding with one another as we frantically seek an escape route.

As we gaze upon the conflict below and the serenity and magnificence above, we find ourselves trapped amidst a dense cluster of dark clouds. This obstructs our path both upwards and downwards. The clouds stand before us like an indestructible barrier, attempting to crush us, yet lacking the ability to do so just yet.

I plead desperately, "Oh, ring, ring, open wide and set us free!" 
Sincerely, Anne

Dear Kitty,

I have thought of a fitting title for this chapter: "Ode to My Beloved Fountain Pen: In Memoriam." My fountain pen was always one of my most cherished possessions. I held it in high regard, particularly because it had a thick nib, which allowed me to write neatly. Its journey throughout its life has been long and fascinating, and I will now provide a summary of its story.

When I was just nine years old, my fountain pen, carefully wrapped in cotton, arrived as a "sample of no commercial value" all the way from Aachen. This generous gift came from my grandmother, who used to reside there.

Please rewrite the given text.

While suffering from the flu, I remained in bed as the strong February winds howled outside the apartment building. Encased in a luxurious red leather case, this magnificent fountain pen was proudly displayed to my girlfriends at the earliest opportunity. As for me, Anne Frank, I reveled in being the fortunate owner of such a prized possession.

At the age of ten, I was given permission to bring a pen to school, and to my astonishment, the teacher even permitted me to write with it. However, when I turned eleven, my cherished possession had to be concealed again, as my sixth-grade teacher mandated the use of only school pens and inkpots. Upon my entrance into the Jewish Lyceum at the age of twelve, my fountain pen was bestowed with a fresh case to commemorate the occasion.

In addition to having space for a pencil, the remarkable feature of my bag was its zipper. Throughout my time in the Annex at thirteen, I carried the fountain pen with me, and we swiftly filled numerous diaries and compositions. As I turned fourteen, my fountain pen accompanied me during its final year of use, until...

As I exited my room and prepared to take a seat at the table to start writing, I was abruptly shoved to the side to accommodate Margot and Father, who wished to practice their Latin. Consequently, the fountain pen that belonged to me remained untouched on the table, while I, feeling disheartened, had to settle for a minuscule portion of the table where I began the task of rubbing beans. It is in this manner that we eliminate mold from the beans and bring them back to their initial condition.

I swept the floor at fifteen minutes before six o'clock. Then, I gathered the dirt and rotten beans, and disposed of them in a newspaper. I tossed the newspaper into the stove and witnessed a magnificent flame shooting up. It was truly amazing to see the stove, which had been struggling, suddenly revive itself. Everything became peaceful once more.
After the Latin students departed, I took a seat at the table to make my selection.
I searched for my fountain pen where I had left it, but it was nowhere to be found no matter where I looked. I took another glance, but still couldn't see it.
Margot, Mother, Father, and Dussel all searched for it, but it had disappeared. Margot proposed, "Perhaps it accidentally fell into the stove, along with the beans!"

I responded, "No, it's impossible!" However, as the evening progressed and my fountain pen remained missing, we all started to believe that it had indeed been burned, especially considering that celluloid is highly flammable. Our worst suspicions were confirmed the following day when Father went to clean out the stove and found the clip, which was used to attach the pen to a pocket, among the ashes.

There was no sign of the gold nib remaining. Father speculated, "Perhaps it melted and fused with the stone." The only solace I have is that my fountain pen was cremated, a fate I hope to experience someday as well!

Sending you my warmest regards,

SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 27, 1943 
Dear Kitty, 
Last night, right before I fell asleep, Hanneli suddenly appeared in front of me.

As I observed her presence, she was adorned in tattered clothing, her face gaunt and tired. Her immense eyes held a combination of sorrow and disapproval, conveying a clear message to me: "Anne, why have you abandoned me? I implore you, save me from this dreadful place!" Regrettably, I am unable to provide assistance to her.

I am left feeling helpless as I witness the suffering and loss of others. My only recourse is to offer prayers to God, pleading for the return of our loved one. In that moment, I solely saw Hanneli and comprehended the reasons behind it.

I made a mistake in assessing her and failed to recognize the challenges she was facing. She was deeply committed to her girlfriend, and it probably appeared as if I was attempting to disrupt their relationship. I can only imagine how terrible she must have felt in that situation.
I understand because I can relate to the feeling! Every now and then, I had moments of clarity, but I would quickly become self-absorbed again, focusing on my own issues and enjoyment.

I deeply regret how I treated her, and now she gazes at me with a helpless expression, her face pale and her eyes pleading. I wish there was something I could do to assist her. It pains me to see fate holding her in its deadly grip while I possess everything I desire.

She possessed the same level of devotion as me, if not stronger, and shared the desire to always do what is morally right. However, I cannot help but question why I have been selected to survive, while she is likely facing death. What sets us apart?

Why have we become so distant from each other? Honestly, I hadn't given her much thought in months, or maybe even a year. I hadn't completely erased her from my mind, but it wasn't until I saw her standing in front of me that I remembered all the pain she had endured.

I sincerely hope, Hanneli, that if you survive the war and come back to us, I will have the opportunity to rectify the harm I have caused you. I struggle to accurately convey my emotions, but the single word "mom" encompasses it all. I wish I could pay tribute to her by eliminating the "s," but it's fortunate that she remains unaware of this desire as it would only bring her unhappiness.

That will suffice. My writing has brought me up from the depths of despair to some extent. Sincerely, Anne. 
Today, the day following Christmas, I cannot refrain from pondering about Pim and the narrative he shared with me during this same time last year. Back then, I didn't grasp the significance of his words as clearly as I do at present.
If he were to bring it up again, I might have a chance to demonstrate that I comprehend it.

I believe Pim shared this with me because he, who is aware of the private secrets of many others, wanted to express his own emotions for a change. Pim rarely discusses his own experiences, and I doubt Margot has any idea about what he has endured. Pim cannot deceive me into believing that he has forgotten about that girl. He will never become like her, but he has become extremely adaptable, despite being aware of her flaws. I aspire to be somewhat similar to him without experiencing the same hardships.
On Friday evening, I experienced a first in my life - receiving a Christmas gift. It was given to me by Mr. Kleiman.

Kugler and the girls had organized a delightful surprise for us. Miep created a mouthwatering Christmas cake adorned with the words "Peace 1944" on top, while Bep contributed a batch of cookies that matched the quality of those made before the war. Once again, everything was beautifully wrapped, adorned with lovely pictures stuck onto the packages. As for the remaining time, the holidays swiftly passed for us. Anne. 
On Wednesday, December 29, 1943, I felt a deep sadness once more.

Once again, Grandma and Hanneli appeared before me. I realized how little we truly comprehended the hardships Grandma endured, yet she always remained kind and displayed genuine curiosity in everything that mattered to us.

It's incredible to consider that throughout that time, she was diligently protecting her dreadful secret. Anne's grandmother, who was battling a terminal illness, was consistently loyal and virtuous, making it unimaginable for her to ever disappoint any of us.
Regardless of the circumstances, no matter how badly I behaved, Grandma always supported me. Grandma, did you truly love me, or were you unable to comprehend me? I am uncertain.

Despite having us, Grandma must have felt lonely. It's possible to experience loneliness even when surrounded by loved ones, as you are still not truly connected to anyone on a deep level. And what about Hanneli?
Is she currently alive? What is her current situation? Dear God, please protect her and guide her back to us.

Hanneli, you serve as a constant reminder of the path I could have taken. I frequently envision myself in your position. However, despite this, I find myself frequently unhappy with the current circumstances. Can you help me understand why?

Is it not expected for me to feel happy, satisfied, and joyful, except when Hanneli and others who are suffering come to mind? I can't help but feel selfish and cowardly. Why do I constantly find myself contemplating and envisioning the most dreadful scenarios, and feeling the urge to scream in terror?

Despite everything, I still lack sufficient faith in God, even though He has blessed me abundantly, far beyond what I deserve. Every day, I continue to make numerous mistakes. The mere thought of the suffering endured by my loved ones can bring me to tears, to the extent that I could spend an entire day crying.

The only thing we can do is pray for God to perform a miracle and save at least some of them. I hope I am praying enough for that!

In the afternoon, I finally had my opportunity. Wanting to treat Margot on her birthday, I first went to get the coffee, and then the potatoes. Upon arriving at Peter's room, he hastily removed his papers from the stairs. I inquired if I should close the trapdoor.

"Of course," he replied, "feel free to go up. When you're finished and wish to return downstairs, simply give a knock and I'll assist you." I expressed my gratitude, ascended the stairs, and dedicated a minimum of ten minutes scouring the barrel for the tiniest potatoes.
I felt a twinge of pain in my back, and the attic felt chilly. Without hesitation, I decided to open the trap-door on my own. To my surprise, he kindly rose from his seat and took the pan from me.

"I gave it my all, but I couldn't find any smaller ones."
"Did you check in the large barrel?"
"Yes, I searched through all of them."
At that moment, I reached the bottom of the stairs, and he inspected the pan of potatoes he was still holding. "Oh, these are actually good," he remarked, and added as he handed me the pan, "Well done!"
While saying this, he gave me a heartfelt, affectionate gaze that filled me with warmth. I could sense his desire to please me, but since he couldn't express it with a lengthy compliment, he conveyed everything through his eyes.

I had a clear understanding of his words and was immensely thankful. The memory of those words and the way he looked still brings me joy. Later, when I went downstairs, my mother mentioned that she needed more potatoes, this time for dinner. I offered to go back upstairs and get them.

Upon entering Peter's room, I offered my apologies for once again interrupting him. While ascending the stairs, he suddenly rose from his seat, positioned himself between the stairs and the wall, and firmly grasped my arm in an attempt to prevent me from proceeding. "Allow me to take care of it," he insisted.

"I have to go upstairs anyway," I stated. However, I reassured him that it wasn't truly required for me to only retrieve the small ones on this occasion. With my persuasive words, he released his grip on my arm. As I made my way back, he proceeded to open the trapdoor and once more claimed the pan from my possession.

I stood by the door and inquired, "What are you currently occupied with?" 
"I'm working on French," he responded. 
Curious, I asked if I could have a glimpse of his lessons. Afterward, I went to wash my hands and settled myself on the divan opposite him.

Once I had provided him with an explanation of some French, our conversation commenced. He expressed his desire to relocate to the Dutch East Indies and reside on a rubber plantation once the war was over. He shared details about his life back home, including involvement in the black market, and expressed feelings of worthlessness and being a burden.

I informed him that he suffered from a significant inferiority complex. He proceeded to discuss the possibility of a war between Russia and England, as well as sharing his thoughts on the Jewish community. He expressed that life would have been simpler had he been a Christian or had the opportunity to convert to Christianity after the war.

I inquired about his interest in being baptized, but that was not his intention either. He expressed that he could never truly embrace Christianity, but once the war was over, he would do everything in his power to hide his Jewish identity. In that moment, I felt a brief pang of sadness.

It is unfortunate that he still retains a hint of dishonesty. Peter expressed his belief that the Jews have always been and will always be the chosen people. In response, I expressed a hope that, for once, they would be chosen for something positive. However, despite this disagreement, we continued to chat amicably about various topics such as our father, the act of judging human character, and numerous other subjects that have slipped my mind. I departed at fifteen minutes past five when Bep arrived.

Later that night, he expressed another pleasant remark. Our conversation revolved around the photo of a famous actor that I had previously gifted him, and it had been adorning his room for over a year and a half. He admired it so greatly that I offered to present him with a few additional ones.

When asked if he wanted a new picture, he declined and stated that he preferred to keep the one he already had. He explained that he looked at it every day and had formed friendships with the people depicted in it. This made me realize why he always hugged Mousch tightly - he also craved affection.

I neglected to mention another point he brought up. He mentioned, "I'm not afraid, except when it pertains to matters concerning myself, but I'm actively addressing that." Peter harbors a significant inferiority complex. As an illustration, he consistently believes he is unintelligent while viewing us as highly intelligent.
Whenever I assist him with French, he expresses his gratitude countless times. One of these days, I intend to tell him, "Enough already! You excel in English and geography!"

Dear Kitty,
This morning, I was upstairs as I had made a promise to Mrs. van D. to read her some of my stories.

I started off by reading "Eva's Dream" to Eva, and she absolutely loved it. Later, I entertained her with a few excerpts from "The Secret Annex," which had her laughing uncontrollably. Peter also joined in for a bit, catching the tail end of the reading session. He expressed his interest in hearing more and invited me to his room sometime for further readings. In that moment, I took a leap of faith and grabbed my notebook, allowing him to read the passage where Cady and Hans discuss their beliefs about God.

I'm unsure about the impact it had on him. He mentioned something that I can't fully recall, not specifically about whether it was positive or negative, but rather about the underlying concept. I simply wanted him to understand that my writing isn't limited to just entertaining topics.

He gave a nod of agreement, and I exited the room. I am eager to find out if there will be any further updates. 
Warm regards, Anne Frank 
FRIDAY, FEBRUARY 18, 1944 
Dear Kitty,

The object of my friendship is consistently present, providing me with a sense of security and eliminating any concern of potential competitors (excluding Margot). It is important to note that I am not in love, but I do have a strong intuition that something wonderful will grow between Peter and myself - a friendship built on trust. Whenever I have the opportunity, I make a point to visit him, and the dynamic has evolved from the initial uncertainty he had towards me.

Contrarily, he continues to talk incessantly while I am preparing to leave. My mother disapproves of me going upstairs, always insisting that I am disturbing Peter and should refrain from bothering him.
Can't she acknowledge my intuition? It's disconcerting how she always gives me strange looks when I visit Peter's room. And when I come back downstairs, she always questions where I've been.

I went upstairs carrying my book and all my belongings, but out of nowhere, tears started welling up again. Quickly, I rushed downstairs to the bathroom, taking the hand mirror with me. I sat on the toilet, still fully dressed, long after I finished, my tears staining the red fabric of my apron. In that moment, I felt completely defeated.

These thoughts crossed my mind: "I might not be able to reach Peter through this method. It's possible that he doesn't even have an affinity towards me and doesn't require anyone to share his feelings with. Perhaps he only sees me as someone casual." Can you please rephrase this text?

I will have to return to my solitude, without anyone to share my thoughts with and without Peter by my side. I will be devoid of hope, comfort, and any anticipation of the future. After a while, I regained hope and became filled with anticipation again, even though I continued to shed tears—internally.

On Sundays, the activities that occur in other people's houses throughout the rest of the week take place here in the Annex. While others dress up and enjoy a leisurely walk in the sunshine, we dedicate our day to cleaning, sweeping, and doing the laundry.
At eight o'clock, while the rest of us enjoy sleeping in,

At eight o'clock, Dussel wakes up and proceeds to the bathroom. After that, he goes downstairs and then returns upstairs. Following that, he heads back to the bathroom, where he spends a full hour taking a shower. It is now nine-thirty.

The stoves have been ignited, the blackout screen has been removed, and Mr. van Daan proceeds to the bathroom. One of my Sunday morning challenges is being forced to remain in bed and gaze at Dussel's back while he prays.

It may sound unusual, but witnessing a praying Dussel is quite distressing. It's not because he sheds tears or becomes emotional, not at all. Instead, he dedicates a whole fifteen minutes to rocking back and forth, from his toes to his heels. Continuously swaying, back and forth.

If I don't close my eyes tightly, my head begins to spin because it seems to continue endlessly. At ten-fifteen, the van Daans whistle, indicating that the bathroom is available. Please rewrite this passage.

In the living quarters of the Frank family, the first drowsy expressions are starting to appear as they wake up from their pillows. Suddenly, everything starts to happen rapidly. Margot and I alternate in taking care of the laundry.

Due to the chilly temperature downstairs, we decided to wear pants and wrap head scarves around ourselves. In the meantime, Father is occupied in the bathroom. Either Margot or I will use the bathroom at eleven, ensuring that we are all clean.
I won't spend much time discussing breakfast at eleven-thirty since there is already enough conversation about food without me adding to it.
At twelve-fifteen, we part ways, each of us going our own direction. Father, dressed in overalls, kneels down and vigorously brushes the rug, causing a cloud of dust to fill the room.

Mr. Dussel is responsible for making the beds, but unfortunately, he consistently does it incorrectly. Throughout the process, he always whistles the same Beethoven violin concerto. Meanwhile, mother can be heard moving around in the attic as she hangs up the laundry.
After putting on his hat, Mr. van Daan goes down to the lower regions, usually accompanied by Peter and Mouschi. Mrs. van Daan then follows suit.

Van D. puts on a lengthy apron, a black wool coat, and overshoes. She wraps a red wool scarf around her head, picks up a pile of soiled laundry, and with a practiced nod of a washerwoman, goes downstairs. Margot and I handle the dishes and tidy up the room.

My beloved Kitty, 
The weather has been delightful since yesterday, and I am feeling much better. My writing, which is my greatest solace, is progressing nicely. Every morning, I visit the attic to refresh my lungs and rid myself of the stagnant air.
When I arrived at the location this morning, Peter was occupied with cleaning up. He completed the task promptly and approached the area where I was seated.

We were captivated by the beautiful sight before us as we sat on our favorite spot on the floor. The clear blue sky, the dew-covered chestnut tree, and the shimmering seagulls and other birds flying through the air mesmerized us. We were so overcome with emotion that we couldn't find words to express ourselves. He leaned his head against a sturdy beam, while I remained seated.

Inhaling deeply, we observed the surroundings and sensed that the enchantment should not be disrupted by conversation. We maintained this silent communion for an extended period, and as he departed to the loft to split firewood, I realized he was a kind and honorable young man. Ascending the ladder to the loft, I trailed behind; throughout the fifteen minutes he spent chopping wood, neither of us uttered a single word.

Observing him from where I stood, it was evident that he was making a sincere effort to chop wood skillfully, showcasing his physical prowess. However, I couldn't help but divert my gaze towards the open window, allowing my eyes to wander across a substantial portion of Amsterdam, spanning across rooftops and eventually reaching the horizon, where a faint, almost indiscernible strip of pale blue resided. Contemplating the scene before me, a thought emerged: "As long as this serene ambiance persists, with its radiant sunlight and cloudless sky, and as long as I can revel in its splendor, how could desolation possibly overtake me?" 
For those who find themselves plagued by fear, solitude, or unhappiness, vent

Only then will you truly sense that everything is in its rightful place and that the divine desires for people to find happiness amidst the splendor and simplicity of nature. As long as this remains, which should be for eternity, I am confident that solace will be found for any sorrow, no matter the situation. I strongly hold the belief that nature has the power to bring solace to all who endure suffering.

I wonder if it will be soon when I can find someone who shares my immense happiness. It would be wonderful to share this feeling with someone who feels the same way. 
From, Anne 
P.S. Thoughts: Regarding Peter.

We have been deprived of many things for a significant amount of time. I long for those things just as much as you do. I am not referring to material possessions, as we are adequately provided for in that aspect; I am talking about the internal aspects.

Similar to you, I have a deep desire for freedom and the invigorating sensation of fresh air. However, I believe we have been adequately compensated for their absence, at least in terms of our inner selves. Today, as I sat by the window and gazed outside, immersing myself in the beauty of God and nature, a profound sense of joy overcame me. I simply felt content and blissful.
Pete r, provided individuals experience such inner contentment, stemming from the bliss of nature, good health, and countless other sources...

Furthermore, one can always reclaim that sense of joy. While material wealth, status, and other external factors may be lost, the inner happiness within one's heart can only be temporarily diminished. It will persist, as long as one is alive, ready to bring happiness once more.

When you experience feelings of loneliness or sadness, consider visiting the loft on a sunny day and directing your gaze outside. Instead of focusing on the houses and rooftops, shift your attention towards the sky. By fearlessly looking at the sky, you will recognize your inner purity and rediscover happiness.

My beloved Kitty, 
Throughout the day, from morning until night, my thoughts are consumed by Peter. His image lingers in my mind as I drift off to sleep, and I find myself dreaming of him and waking up to his gaze. 
I cannot shake the overwhelming sense that Peter and I are not as dissimilar as we may appear at first glance. The reason for this is that neither he nor I have a mother.

He is excessively shallow, enjoys flirting, and pays little attention to his own thoughts. My partner, on the other hand, shows genuine interest in my life but lacks tact, sensitivity, and a maternal understanding. Both Peter and I are grappling with our deepest emotions.

We lack confidence and are emotionally fragile, making us too sensitive to handle harsh treatment. When faced with such situations, my instinct is to escape or conceal my emotions. Instead, I express my frustration by making noise, banging pots and pans, splashing water, and generally being disruptive, causing everyone to wish I were far away.

Peter's response is to withdraw, speak sparingly, remain silent, and indulge in daydreams, all while concealing his authentic nature. 
However, when and in what manner will we ultimately connect with one another? 
I am uncertain how much longer I can maintain this restraint on my longing.

Monday, February 28, 1944

It feels like a never-ending nightmare that continues even when I am awake. I come across him almost every hour, but I am unable to be with him openly or let others notice. Peter Schiff and Peter van Daan have merged into a single person named Peter, who is both gentle and kind, and whom I yearn for desperately.

My mother is terrible, but my father is nice, which only makes him more frustrating. Margot is the worst because she manipulates me, taking advantage of my friendly demeanor to claim me as her own, even though all I desire is solitude. Peter did not come with me to the attic; instead, he went to the loft to do some carpentry. With each rasp and bang, my courage crumbled, and my unhappiness grew even stronger.

The sound of a clock tolling in the distance carried the message of "Be pure in heart, be pure in mind!"
