Dear Kitty, 
Today, Margot and I spent time together in the attic. However, I can't fully appreciate our time together because I can't help but imagine how it would be if I were with Peter or someone else. I believe Margot feels the same way about many things as I do.
During dishwashing, Bep initiated a conversation with Mother and Mrs. van Daan regarding her feelings of discouragement. What assistance did the two of them provide to her?

Our tactless mother, in particular, only exacerbated the situation. Can you guess what advice she offered? She suggested that she should consider all the other individuals around the globe who are experiencing hardship!

How can considering the suffering of others be beneficial when you are feeling miserable yourself? I expressed a similar sentiment, but their response was to advise me to avoid engaging in such conversations.
The adults are incredibly foolish! It's as if Peter, Margot, Bep, and I don't all experience the same emotions. The only solace lies in the affection of a mother or an exceptionally intimate friend.
These two mothers lack understanding about who we are.
Mrs. van Daan is more expressive than Mother. I really wish I had been able to offer some words of comfort to poor Bep, something that I know would have been helpful based on my own experiences.

However, my father intervened and forcefully shoved me aside. It's frustrating how everyone is so foolish! Additionally, I discussed with Margot about the possibility of our life being more pleasant here if our parents weren't so bothersome.
We could arrange evenings where everyone has the opportunity to discuss a specific topic, but we have already done that before. It is difficult for me to engage in conversation here.
Mr. van Daan becomes aggressive, Mother adopts a sarcastic tone and cannot speak in a normal manner, Father lacks the motivation to participate, as does Mr. Dussel, and Mrs. remains silent.
Van D. is frequently targeted to the point where they sit passively, their face turning red, and they are barely able to defend themselves. How does this situation affect us?
It seems that we are not permitted to express our opinions. How progressive of them! To be forbidden from having an opinion!

Although people may tell you to be quiet, they cannot prevent you from forming your own opinion. Regardless of age, it is impossible to prohibit someone from having their own perspective. The only thing that would truly benefit Bep, Margot, Peter, and myself is genuine love and dedication, which is lacking in this place.

No one, particularly the ignorant sages in this vicinity, possesses the ability to comprehend us. We are far more perceptive and intellectually superior than they could ever fathom. Love, the concept of love, is not easily defined by mere words. Can you please rephrase this passage?

Love involves comprehending and empathizing with someone, demonstrating concern for their well-being, and partaking in both their moments of happiness and sadness. Ultimately, this encompasses a physical aspect of love. It entails the act of giving and receiving, regardless of one's marital status or whether or not they have children.

It is not important to lose your innocence, as long as you have someone by your side who truly understands you and is exclusively yours for the rest of your life. This is what matters to me, Anne M. Frank. Currently, my mother is complaining at me once again, likely out of jealousy because I talk to Mrs.
I don't care about Mrs. van Daan's feelings, as I am more concerned about my own. Today, I was able to contact Peter and we had a conversation that lasted for at least forty-five minutes.

He had difficulty sharing something personal about himself, but eventually managed to express it after a considerable amount of time. I was uncertain about whether it was more beneficial for me to remain or depart.

I was really eager to assist him! I informed him about Bep and the lack of sensitivity that our mothers have. He shared with me that his parents argue non-stop, covering topics like politics and smoking, among other things.

As I mentioned earlier, Peter is quite shy, although he is not too shy to confess that he would be completely content without seeing his parents for a year or two. "Despite his pleasant appearance, my father isn't as kind as he seems," he explained. "However, when it comes to the issue of smoking, my mother is absolutely correct."

I shared with him the details about my mother, but he immediately defended my father, considering him to be a "wonderful person." 
Later, as I finished washing the dishes and was about to take off my apron, he motioned for me to come closer and requested that I keep quiet about his parents' ongoing arguments and them not speaking to each other.
I made a promise, even though I had already informed Margot. However, I am confident that Margot will keep it to herself. I assured Peter, saying, "Don't worry about me, Peter."

I have come to understand the importance of keeping information confidential. I make sure not to share everything I hear with others. When I informed him about this, he was pleased to hear it. I also mentioned that we tend to gossip a lot and agreed with Margot's observation that I am not always honest because, despite my desire to stop gossiping, I still find great enjoyment in discussing Mr.

"Dussel," he stated. "I appreciate your honesty." He turned red, and his genuine compliment made me feel slightly embarrassed as well. After that, we continued discussing the topics of "upstairs" and "downstairs."

Peter was quite surprised to learn that he dislikes his parents. "Peter," I said, "I always strive to be truthful, so I see no reason to withhold this from you. We can acknowledge their imperfections as well." I continued, "Peter, I genuinely want to assist you.

Can I offer my assistance? I can sense that you're in an uncomfortable position, and even though you haven't said anything, I can tell it bothers you."
"Oh, I appreciate your help!" 
"Perhaps it would be better for you to speak with Father. You can confide in him without worrying about him sharing it with others."
"I know, he's a great friend." 
"You really admire him, don't you?" 
Peter nodded and I added, "Well, he thinks highly of you too, you know!" 
He looked up suddenly and blushed.

It was truly heartwarming to witness the immense joy these few words brought him. 
"Do you really believe that?" he inquired.

"I can tell," I responded, "by the subtle remarks he occasionally makes." 
Afterwards, Mr. van Daan entered to conduct some dictation.

Peter is a wonderful person, just like Father! 
Love, Anne M. Frank

Peter didn't mention anything else about his parents; our conversation revolved around books and past experiences. "I said," I replied.

He simply responded with, "Oh, I don't mind!" It is difficult to determine how much of his answer was influenced by shyness. I sound like a person who is deeply in love and can only discuss their beloved.

I hope we'll have the courage to express ourselves more openly. Perhaps that opportunity will arise sooner than expected! Every now and then, he shares a meaningful look with me, and I respond with a playful wink, bringing joy to both of us.

SATURDAY, MARCH 4, 1944 
Dear Kitty, 
Today is the first Saturday in a long time that hasn't felt tiresome, dull, and monotonous.

The reason for the change in plans is because of Peter. Instead of going to the attic to hang up my apron, Father asked if I wanted to stay and practice my French, and I agreed. We conversed in French for a bit, and I also took the opportunity to explain something to Peter. Afterward, we focused on improving our English skills.

My father was reading aloud from Dickens, and I was filled with immense joy. This was because I had the privilege of sitting on Father's chair, right next to Peter. At quarter to eleven, I descended the stairs. Upon returning at eleven-thirty, I found Peter eagerly waiting for me on the staircase.

We conversed until fifteen minutes to one. On occasions when I exit the room, such as after a meal, and Peter finds an opportunity where no one else can overhear, he bids me farewell, saying, "Goodbye, Anne, see you later." 
I am filled with joy! I ponder if he might finally develop romantic feelings for me.

Regardless of the situation, he is a pleasant young man, and you cannot comprehend the joy I feel when I converse with him! 
Mrs. van D.

I believe it is acceptable for me to communicate with Peter, but today she playfully asked me, "Can I rely on both of you being together?" 
"Absolutely," I objected. "I consider that remark offensive!" 
Every day, at every hour, I eagerly anticipate seeing Peter.
This is Anne M. Frank writing. By the way, I wanted to mention that there was a beautiful layer of snow covering everything last night.

Now that it has melted and hardly anything remains. 
Dearest Kitty, 
Since Peter confided in me about his parents, I have felt a peculiar sense of duty towards him. Don't you find that odd? It's as if their arguments are just as relevant to me as they are to him. However, I am reluctant to bring it up anymore as I fear it might make him uneasy.
I would never want to intrude, even if I were offered all the money in existence. Peter's expression indicates that he contemplates things as profoundly as I do. Yesterday, I felt irritated when Mrs.
Van D. expressed disbelief, saying, "The thinker!" Peter became visibly embarrassed, and I felt a surge of anger. Why can't these individuals refrain from speaking unnecessarily?

It is difficult to comprehend the feeling of being on the sidelines, witnessing his loneliness and being helpless to intervene. I can empathize with his despondency and the emotional toll that conflicts and love must take on him.
Peter is in need of a great amount of love! It was quite disheartening to hear him reject the idea of having friends. His belief is completely misguided.

I doubt his sincerity. He holds onto his masculinity, his preference for being alone, and his pretense of not caring in order to uphold his image, ensuring he never has to reveal his emotions. I feel sorry for Peter, wondering how much longer he can keep this façade going.
Will he not burst from this extraordinary effort? Oh, Peter, if only I had the ability to assist you, if only you would allow me! Together, we could overcome our feelings of isolation and solitude.

I have been contemplating a lot, but not expressing many words. I feel joyous when I encounter him, and even more elated if the sun is shining during our time together. I cleansed my hair yesterday, and due to the knowledge of him being nearby, I was quite lively and exuberant.
I couldn't control it; the more I try to be calm and serious internally, the more boisterous I become externally!

Who will be the first to find a weakness in my defenses? It's fortunate that the van Daans do not have a daughter, as my conquest would never be as stimulating, captivating, and pleasant with someone of the same gender.

Yours sincerely, Anne M. Frank
PS. I value our honesty, and I feel it's important to inform you that my life revolves around each new meeting or interaction.

I constantly wish to find out that he is eagerly anticipating our meeting, and I become ecstatic when I notice his shy efforts. I believe he desires to be able to express himself as effortlessly as I do; little does he realize that it is his awkwardness that I find endearing.

He replied, "By maintaining a cheerful demeanor." 
This was the most pleasant comment he made throughout the evening. He also mentioned that he didn't have any objections to me visiting his room like I used to; in fact, he enjoyed it.

I also expressed to him that the affectionate names our parents use for each other hold no real significance, and that a few kisses here and there do not automatically build trust. We also discussed the importance of pursuing our own paths, the diary, feelings of isolation, the contrast between our true selves and how we present ourselves to others, and my tendency to wear a metaphorical mask. The conversation was truly delightful.

I believe he has developed a fondness for me as a friend, and for now, that is sufficient. I am incredibly thankful and overjoyed, but I am struggling to express my emotions adequately. I must apologize, Kitty, as my writing is not as impressive as usual today.

I have a sense that Peter and I have a shared secret. Each time he gazes at me with those eyes, that smile, and gives a wink, it ignites a spark within me. I desire for our current state to remain unchanged, and for us to create countless joyous moments together in the future.

On Monday, March 20, 1944, I, Anne, am filled with gratitude and happiness. Today, Peter approached me and kindly requested my presence for another evening. He assured me that my presence would not be a bother to him and suggested that if there was enough space for one person, there was surely enough space for two. However, I expressed my inability to meet him every evening as my parents did not approve of the idea. Nonetheless, Peter advised me not to let their opinion bother me.

I informed him that I would be interested in visiting on a Saturday evening and also inquired about his availability to observe the moon. He responded positively, suggesting that we could go downstairs to view it. I agreed, despite my slight concerns about potential burglars. However, my happiness has been overshadowed by a sense of unease.

I have had a persistent feeling that Margot has feelings for Peter for a while now. I am unsure of the extent of her feelings, but the entire situation is causing me great discomfort. Whenever I visit Peter, I unintentionally cause pain to Margot.

It's amusing because she rarely displays it. Even though I would be extremely jealous, Margot simply tells me not to pity her. "I find it terrible that you've become the only one who is different," I commented.

"I've grown accustomed to it," she responded with a hint of bitterness. Telling Peter is out of the question for now. Perhaps I'll bring it up later, but there are countless other matters we must discuss before that.

Last night, I was slapped by my mother, and I admit that I deserved it. I should not let my indifference and disrespect towards her go too far. Despite everything, I need to make an effort to be friendly and refrain from making negative comments.
Even though Pim used to be nicer, he has been making an effort not to treat me as a child. However, his behavior has now become too distant. Only time will tell what the outcome will be.

He has issued a warning, stating that unless I complete my algebra, I will not receive any tutoring once the war is over. I have the option to wait and observe the outcome, but I would prefer to commence again, as long as I am provided with a new book.

I have reached my limit for now. All I do is stare at Peter, and my heart is completely full! 
Sincerely, Anne M.
Frank acknowledges that he wasn't completely truthful when he claimed to not be jealous of Anne. However, he clarifies that his lack of jealousy applies to both Anne and Peter.

I apologize for not having found someone to confide in and it seems unlikely that I will find someone in the near future. However, this is why I truly hope that both of you can trust each other. There are many things here that you are currently missing out on, things that others often overlook.

However, in contrast, I am confident that I would not have made as much progress with Peter. This is because I believe I would require a strong emotional connection with someone before I am comfortable sharing my thoughts. I would want to be certain that they truly comprehend me, even without me expressing much verbally. Therefore, it would have to be someone who I perceive as intellectually superior to me, which is not the case with Peter.

I understand that you might feel a connection with him, but please don't blame yourself for thinking that you are taking something away from me that I deserve. That is not the case at all. In fact, both you and Peter can benefit greatly from your friendship.

Dear Margot,

I greatly appreciate your thoughtful letter, but I must admit that I am still not entirely content with the situation, and I doubt that I ever will be.

Currently, Peter and I do not possess the level of trust that you seem to believe. It is simply that when you find yourself standing next to an open window during the dark hours of the night, there is an opportunity to communicate more deeply than in the presence of bright sunlight.

Thank you for understanding.

Best regards,
[Your Name]

Expressing your feelings through whispers is often easier than shouting them from rooftops. It seems that you have developed a sisterly affection for Peter and desire to aid him, much like I do. Maybe one day, you will have the opportunity to do so, although that is not the type of trust we are currently referring to. Please provide a rephrased version of this text.

I am of the opinion that trust needs to be mutual, which is likely why my father and I have never developed a strong bond. However, let's not dwell on this topic any longer. If there is anything else you would like to discuss, please write it down as I find it easier to express myself on paper rather than in person.

I hope that some of your goodness and my father's goodness will rub off on me because, in that way, the two of you are similar. 
With love, Anne 
WEDNESDAY, MARCH 22, 1944 
Dearest Kitty, 
Last night, I received a letter from Margot that said: 
Dear Anne, 
After reading your letter from yesterday, I get the sense that you feel guilty whenever you go to Peter's to work or talk. But there is really no need for that. Deep down, I know there's someone who I can trust (just as he can trust me), and I wouldn't be able to tolerate Peter in his place.
Nevertheless, as you mentioned, I perceive Peter as akin to a brother.

My younger brother and I have been testing the waters, but we haven't reached a point where we have a strong brotherly or sisterly bond. So, there's no need for you to pity me. Now that you have found companionship, make the most of it and enjoy it to the fullest.

Currently, the situation here is becoming increasingly delightful. It appears that genuine affection might be blossoming in the Annex. The countless jests about marrying Peter if we remained here for an extended period no longer seem so foolish.
I have no intentions of marrying him, just so you know. I cannot predict how he will turn out as he grows older, or if we will develop strong enough feelings for each other to consider marriage.

I am confident that Peter has feelings for me as well, but I am uncertain about the nature of those feelings. I am unsure if he sees me as just a good friend, or if he is attracted to me romantically or as a sisterly figure. His comment about how I always supported him during his parents' arguments brought me immense joy, as it indicated progress towards establishing a strong friendship between us.

Yesterday, I asked him what he would do if numerous Annes kept unexpectedly visiting him. His response was, "If they were all similar to you, it wouldn't be so unpleasant." He is exceptionally welcoming, and it appears that he genuinely enjoys my company. In the meantime, he has been diligently studying French, even continuing his studies in bed until ten-fifteen. Reflecting on our conversation and the way we spoke to each other on Saturday night, I feel a sense of contentment within myself for the first time. To clarify, I still hold the same sentiments and wouldn't change my stance.

I desire to alter something, using my usual approach. He possesses such striking looks, whether he is engaged in an activity or simply being still. He exudes kindness, goodness, and remarkable beauty.

One thing that caught him off guard was realizing that I am not the superficial and worldly Anne that I may seem to be. Instead, he discovered that I am a dreamer just like him, dealing with my own share of troubles. After we finished dinner last night, I waited for him to invite me upstairs, but nothing happened, so I eventually left.

He descended the stairs to inform Dussel that it was time to tune in to the radio, but he lingered in the vicinity of the bathroom for some time. However, as Dussel took an excessive amount of time, he returned upstairs. He anxiously paced back and forth in his room and retired to bed earlier than usual. 
Throughout the entire evening, I felt such restlessness that I repeatedly visited the bathroom to refresh myself with cold water on my face.

I spent some time reading, letting my mind wander, and occasionally glancing at the clock, anxiously waiting. The sound of his footsteps kept me company throughout. Feeling tired, I decided to go to bed early.
Now, I need to bathe tonight. As for tomorrow...

Dear Margot,
It appears that tomorrow is still quite distant. At this moment, I believe it would be most prudent to exercise patience and observe the unfolding events. 
Kind regards, 
Anne M. Frank

It won't be much longer until Peter and I are faced with a decision - whether to return to our previous state or explore other possibilities. The outcome is uncertain, as I can only see as far as my immediate surroundings. However, one thing is clear: if Peter and I do become friends again, I will inform him that you hold a strong affection for him and are willing to provide assistance if he requires it.

I understand that you may not want me to, but I am indifferent to your opinion. I am unsure of Peter's thoughts about you, but I will inquire when the opportunity arises. Rest assured, it is nothing negative - quite the opposite! You are invited to join us in the attic or wherever we may be. Could you please rephrase this text?

We have a mutual understanding to only communicate during the evenings when it's dark, so you won't be interrupting us. Stay positive! I'm putting in my best effort, even though it can be challenging at times.

Dear Kitty,
I am happy to report that things have returned to normal here. Our coupon men have been released from prison, which is a great relief. Miep has returned since yesterday, but today her husband fell ill with chills and fever, displaying the typical symptoms of the flu.
Despite Bep's improvement, she still has a cough, and Mr. Kleiman will need to remain at home for an extended period. A nearby plane crash occurred yesterday.

The crew successfully parachuted out in time before the crash, which unfortunately happened on a school building. Fortunately, no children were present inside at the time. A minor fire broke out, resulting in the unfortunate loss of a few lives.

As the airmen descended, the Germans rained bullets upon them. The Amsterdammers who witnessed this were filled with anger at such a despicable act. We, specifically the ladies, were also terrified beyond measure.

I really dislike the sound of gunfire. 
Now, let's talk about me. 
Yesterday, I was with Peter and, for some reason, I genuinely don't know why, we ended up discussing the topic of sex. 
Please provide an alternative wording for this passage.

I had decided a while back that I would approach him with a few inquiries. He possesses extensive knowledge; when I mentioned our lack of information to him, he was astounded. I shared a great deal about Margot and myself, as well as our parents, and expressed my apprehension in seeking answers from them recently.

He kindly offered to educate me, and I happily agreed. He explained the mechanics of contraceptives, and I confidently inquired about the signs of maturity in boys. It took him a moment to ponder, but he promised to provide an answer later tonight. I shared the unfortunate experience of Jacque and expressed that girls are vulnerable when faced with powerful boys.

"He reassured me, saying that there was no need to fear him," he stated. 
Later that evening, upon my return, he shared his insights on boys, which was slightly embarrassing, 
but still incredibly comforting to have the opportunity to talk about it with him.

Neither he nor I had ever imagined that we would be able to have such open discussions with a girl or a boy about intimate topics. I feel like I have gained a deep understanding now. He shared a lot with me about what he referred to as "Prasentivmitteln" (which should actually be "Praservativmitteln" in German, meaning prophylactics).
In the bathroom that night, Margot and I engaged in a conversation about Bra m and Trees, who happened to be two friends of hers.

This morning, I received an unpleasant surprise when Pe ter called me upstairs after breakfast. He expressed his disappointment, saying that I had played a deceitful prank on him. He claimed to have overheard the conversation between Margot and me in the bathroom last night.

It seemed like your intention was solely to test Peter's knowledge and then derive amusement from it!" I was completely taken aback! I made every effort to dissuade him from this absurd notion; I empathized with his emotions, but it was simply not accurate! "Oh dear, Peter," I exclaimed.

"I could never be so cruel. I assured you that I would not share anything you told me, and I will keep that promise. It is disheartening to witness someone put on a facade only to intentionally act in such a hurtful manner."
"It wouldn't be fair if you don't believe me. I promise I didn't say anything. Can't you trust me?" He reassured me that he did, but I feel like we will need to revisit this topic in the future.
I have spent the entire day consumed by worry about it. Thankfully, he openly expressed what was on his mind. Consider the possibility of him harboring the belief that I could be that cruel.

He is incredibly kind! 
Now I feel compelled to share everything with him! 
With love, Anne 
Friday, March 24, 1944 
Dear Kitty, 
Lately, I frequently find myself going to Peter's room after dinner to enjoy the cool evening breeze.

Engaging in meaningful conversations can be achieved more swiftly in the darkness compared to the sun gently touching your face. It feels warm and comfortable sitting next to him on a chair and gazing out the window. The van Daans and Dussel tend to make silly comments when I retreat into his room.

They say "Annes zweite Heimat,"* or "Is it appropriate for a man to have young girls in his room at night with the lights off?" Peter handles these supposed jokes with impressive composure. By the way, my mother is also very curious and eager to ask what we talk about, but she's afraid I might decline to answer. Peter believes that the adults are simply envious of our youth and advises us not to let their unpleasant remarks affect us.

Occasionally, he descends the stairs to fetch me, but that situation is uncomfortable as well, as despite his efforts, his face flushes and he struggles to articulate his words. I am relieved that I do not experience blushing; it must be quite unpleasant.

Additionally, it troubles me that Margot is relegated to sitting alone downstairs, while I am upstairs enjoying Peter's company. However, I am unsure of what actions I can take to address this situation. I would not mind if she joined us, but she would simply feel out of place, sitting there without any engagement.

I have been subjected to endless comments about our unexpected friendship. It is remarkable how frequently the discussions during meals revolve around the possibility of a wedding in the Annex, in case the war continues for another five years. Are we paying any attention to these casual conversations among parents?
It's difficult to understand why everything seems so silly. I can't help but wonder if my parents have simply forgotten that they were young once too.

Regardless, they mock us when we're being sincere, while they take things seriously when we're just joking. 
The future is uncertain, and I'm unsure if we'll reach a point where we have nothing left to say. 
However, if things continue in this manner, we will eventually achieve a level of closeness where words are unnecessary.

It seems that his parents' peculiar behavior would cease if they were not opposed to my frequent presence. Peter and I deliberately keep our conversations undisclosed from them, presumably because they would disapprove of the intimate topics we discuss.

I would like to inquire with Peter about his knowledge of female anatomy. It appears that understanding male anatomy is relatively straightforward, as it can be easily observed in photographs or images of nude males. However, the situation is different when it comes to females.
Women have their genitals concealed between their legs. Peter most likely has never had a close encounter with a girl, and to be honest, neither have I.
Boys are generally easier to understand and describe, but when it comes to describing a girl's anatomy, it seems apparent that he lacks knowledge of the precise details and how everything connects.

He was referring to the cervix, also known as the "Muttermund," which is located on the inside and not visible. The female anatomy is generally well organized. It wasn't until I reached the age of eleven or twelve that I became aware of the presence of a second set of labia on the inside, as they are not visible externally.

It's even more amusing that I mistakenly believed that urine was expelled from the clitoris. Once, I asked my Mother about that small bump, and she claimed to be unaware. She certainly knows how to act clueless when she desires!
Returning to the topic, how can one possibly describe the appearance without the use of models? Would it be worth attempting regardless?

When in an upright position, the only visible thing in front of you is hair. Between your legs, there are two plush, hairy objects that come together when standing, obstructing the view of what is inside.
When you sit down, they separate, and they have a reddish and fleshy interior. The upper part, located between the outer layer, is particularly noticeable.

There is a fold of skin that, upon closer examination, appears similar to a blister. This is referred to as the clitoris. Following that are the inner labia, which are also pressed together, creating a crease.

When they are opened, a small fleshy mound is revealed, no larger than the top of my thumb. The upper section contains a few small holes, serving as the exit for urine. The lower section appears to be mere skin, but that is where the vagina is situated.

The opening is difficult to locate due to the folds of skin concealing it. The size of the hole is so minuscule that it is challenging to comprehend how a person could enter, let alone how a baby could be born from it. Even attempting to insert your index finger proves to be a difficult task.

That's the entirety of what exists, but it holds immense significance! 
With love, Anne M. Frank 
Saturday, March 25, 1944 
Beloved Kitty, 
One only truly comprehends the extent of personal transformation once it has already occurred. 
Kindly rephrase this passage.

I have undergone a significant transformation, with every aspect of myself experiencing a complete shift - my beliefs, thoughts, and ability to analyze. Both internally and externally, nothing remains unchanged. I can confidently say, as it is the truth, that I have changed for the positive.

I previously mentioned that it was difficult for me to adapt to the harsh reality of adults and criticism, considering I had been admired for many years. However, I attribute a significant portion of having to endure such challenges to my Father and Mother. While they wanted me to have a joyful life at home, it would have been better if they hadn't encouraged me to always side with them and only presented their perspective on conflicts and rumors.

It took a while for me to realize that the score was evenly split. I have now come to understand that both young and old have made numerous mistakes here. The greatest error my parents made in their interactions with the van Daans is that they never showed sincerity and warmth, even if they had to pretend.

Most importantly, my desire is to maintain peace and avoid both arguments and gossip. This is not a challenge with Father and Mar, but it is with Mother, which is why I appreciate it when she occasionally scolds me. You can succeed, Mr.
To align with van Daan, it is important to show agreement by actively listening, remaining quiet, and refraining from saying much, if anything at all.
Mrs. Van D, kindly rephrase the text to respond to his teasing and his cheesy jokes with a joke of your own.

One way to win her over is through open communication and being willing to admit when you're wrong. Similarly, she is also honest about her own flaws, of which she has quite a few. It is evident that her perception of me has improved since our initial interactions.

I believe in being honest and expressing my thoughts directly to people, even if it may not be flattering. I value honesty as it allows for personal growth and a sense of self-assurance. Just yesterday, Mrs. [last name] can attest to this.
Van D. mentioned the rice that we provided to Mr. Kleiman.
"We constantly engage in giving, giving, giving. However, there comes a point where I believe that there should be a limit. If only he would accept."
Why should we give away all of our supplies when Mr. Kleiman can find his own rice?
"We require them just as desperately," I countered, disagreeing with Mrs. van Daan.
It is possible that Mr. Kleiman can acquire some rice, but he dislikes the burden of concern it brings. It is not appropriate for us to criticize those who are aiding us.

If we have the ability to do so, we should provide them with whatever they require, even if it means sacrificing one plate of rice each week. The impact of this small change in our diet is minimal, as we can always consume beans instead.

She didn't agree with my perspective, but she mentioned that despite her disagreement, she was willing to compromise, which was a completely separate issue. I have expressed my thoughts sufficiently. At times, I am aware of my position, while other times I have uncertainties, but eventually, I will achieve my desired destination.

With Peter's support, I am confident that I will overcome difficult times and find solace even on gloomy days. Though I am unsure of the depth of his affection and whether we will ever share a kiss, I am not eager to rush or pressure our relationship.

I informed my father about my frequent visits to Peter and asked for his approval, which he gladly granted. This has made it easier for me to confide in Peter about things I would typically keep to myself. For instance, I expressed my desire to pursue writing in the future, and even if I cannot become a full-time writer, I would still incorporate writing into my professional life. Although I lack wealth, material possessions, beauty, intelligence, or cleverness, I am content with my life and have no plans to change that.

From the moment of my birth, happiness has resided within me. I possess a genuine affection for others, a trusting disposition, and a sincere desire for everyone's happiness. With utmost sincerity, your devoted friend, Anne M. Frank. 
A day devoid of any purpose, despite its clear and radiant appearance, holds no less darkness than a night.

(I wrote this a few weeks ago and it is no longer relevant, but I included it because 
my poems are so infrequent.) 
MONDAY, MARCH 27, 1944 
Dearest Kitty, 
We should dedicate a significant portion of our chronicle on our concealed existence to politics, but I have been hesitant to do so.

I usually avoid discussing the subject of politics as it doesn't interest me much. However, in today's letter, I will focus solely on this topic. It is understandable that there are diverse opinions on politics, especially during times of war, leading to frequent discussions.
Engaging in excessive political arguments is simply foolish!

Allow them to laugh, swear, make bets, grumble, and engage in any other activities as long as they remain absorbed in their own thoughts. However, it is best to prevent them from arguing as it only exacerbates the situation. The individuals who come from external sources often bring us a plethora of news that later turns out to be false; nevertheless, our radio has always been truthful thus far.

Jan, Miep, Mr. Kleiman, Bep, and Mr. Kugler experience fluctuations in their political emotions, with Jan being the least affected. 
Please provide an alternative wording for the text.

The atmosphere in the Annex remains constant. There are continuous debates about the invasion, air raids, speeches, and so on. These debates are accompanied by countless exclamations like "Impossible!" and "For heaven's sake!" If these debates are just beginning, how long will they last? Some people think things are going well, while others are more skeptical. Optimists, pessimists, and realists all express their opinions with unwavering energy, each believing they hold the ultimate truth.

A particular woman is irritated by her spouse's unwavering trust in the British, while a certain husband becomes aggressive towards his wife due to her playful and disrespectful comments about his cherished country! And so it continues incessantly from morning till night; the amusing aspect is that they never tire of it. I have stumbled upon a technique, and its impact is staggering, much like poking someone with a pin and observing their reaction.

This is how it works: I initiate a discussion about politics, and it only takes one question, word, or sentence before the whole family gets involved! It seems like the German "Wehrmacht News" and the English BBC aren't sufficient, as they have now introduced special air-raid announcements.
Splendid, but on the flip side, the British Air Force is working constantly. Similar to the German propaganda machine, which is producing falsehoods nonstop! Can you please rephrase this passage?

Every morning at eight, the radio is turned on, sometimes even earlier, and it remains on throughout the day until nine, ten, or even eleven at night. This peculiar habit not only demonstrates the adults' remarkable patience but also suggests that their brains may have become somewhat dull (although I certainly don't want to offend anyone). Ideally, a single broadcast, or at most two, should suffice for the entire day.

I've already expressed everything I wanted to say. "Music While You Work," the Dutch broadcast from England, features either Frank Phillips or Queen Wilhelmina taking turns to captivate a receptive audience. When the adults are not occupied with eating or sleeping, they gather around the radio engaging in conversations about food, rest, and politics.

Wow! It's starting to become really dull, and I'm struggling to prevent myself from becoming a boring old woman too! Although, considering all the elderly people around me, maybe that wouldn't be such a terrible thing!

At nine o'clock on a Sunday evening, as the teapot sits snugly under its cozy on the table, the room fills with guests. This serves as a shining example, a speech delivered by our beloved Winston Churchill.
Dussel occupies the left side of the radio, with Mr. van D. positioned directly in front of it, and Peter situated to the side.
Mar and I are sitting in the last row, while Pim is at the table in front of us. Although my description of our seating arrangements may not be very clear, it is not important.

The men are smoking while Peter finds it difficult to keep his eyes open as he listens. Mama is wearing a long, dark negligee, Mrs. van D. is shaking due to the planes flying towards Essen, unaffected by the conversation. Father is noisily drinking his tea, and Margot and I are brought together like sisters by the presence of the sleeping Mouschi, who has claimed both of our laps.

Margot has curlers in her hair, and my nightgown is uncomfortably small, tight, and short. Despite this, the scene appears intimate, cozy, and peaceful, which is a rare occurrence. However, I can't help but feel anxious as I anticipate the end of the speech.

They are eager, pulling at the leash to initiate another argument! Quietly, like a cat enticing a mouse out of its hiding place, they provoke each other into quarrels and disagreements. 
With love, Anne 
Tuesday, March 28, 1944 
My beloved Kitty, 
Although I would love to write more about politics, I have plenty of other updates to share today.

To begin with, my mother has practically prohibited me from going up to Peter's place because she believes that Mrs. van Daan is envious. Furthermore, Peter has extended an invitation to Margot to join us upstairs.

I am uncertain whether he genuinely intends it or is merely expressing it as a gesture of courtesy. Additionally, I inquired Father about whether I should pay attention to Mrs. van Daan's jealousy, to which he replied that I need not.

What should I do at this moment? My mother is upset and doesn't want me to go upstairs. She wants me to return to doing my homework in the room I share with Dussel. It's possible that she may be feeling jealous.

Margot and I get along so well that even our father doesn't mind us spending a few hours together. He thinks it's nice. Although Margot also likes Peter, she believes that three people can't engage in the same conversations as two.

In addition, my mother believes that Peter has feelings for me. Honestly, I wish this were true because it would level the playing field, making it easier for us to become acquainted with one another.
In addition, she asserts that he consistently gazes at me. Well, I guess we do exchange the occasional wink. However, it's not my fault if he continues to admire my dimples, right?
I find myself in a challenging situation where there is a constant conflict between my mother and me, with both of us opposing each other. Meanwhile, my father chooses to ignore the ongoing tension.

My mother is feeling sad because she still has love for me, but I am not affected by it as she no longer holds any significance in my life. 
Regarding Peter...
I am unwilling to let him go because he is incredibly kind and I hold him in high esteem.
Why are the elderly interfering in our relationship once more? Despite this, I am skilled at concealing my emotions and not revealing how deeply I care for him. Will he ever express his thoughts?

Will I ever experience the sensation of his cheek touching mine, similar to how I felt Petel's cheek in my dream? Oh, Peter and Petel, you are essentially the same person! Others fail to comprehend us; they could never comprehend that we find solace in simply being next to each other without uttering a single word.
They lack any understanding of what brings us closer! When will we conquer these challenges? However, it is beneficial that we must overcome them as it amplifies the beauty of the end.

When he rests his head on his arms and closes his eyes, he still displays his childlike nature. When he engages with Mouschi or talks about her, his love is evident. When he carries heavy loads like potatoes, he showcases his strength. When he courageously observes the gunfire or fearlessly explores the dark house in search of burglars, his bravery shines through. And when he is awkward and clumsy, he becomes irresistibly endearing. It is much more pleasant when he explains something to me rather than me having to teach him. I wish he were superior to me in almost every aspect!
Why should we concern ourselves with our two mothers? If only he would speak up. My father always accuses me of being conceited, but I'm not, I'm just self-assured! Can you please rephrase this text?

I haven't received many compliments about my appearance, except for a boy at school who once told me that I looked adorable when I smiled. Yesterday, Peter gave me a genuine compliment, and just for fun, I'll give you a general idea of our conversation. 
Peter frequently tells me to smile, which I found peculiar. So, I decided to ask him yesterday, "Why do you always tell me to smile?"

"Do you expect me to always have a smile on my face? It's because I have dimples in my cheeks. Can you tell me how you get dimples?" 
"I naturally have them since birth, and I also have one on my chin." 
Can you please rephrase this text?

"It's the only aspect of beauty I have."
"No, I disagree!"
"Yes, it's true. I acknowledge that I am not beautiful. I have never been, and I never will be!"
"I hold a different opinion."

"I believe you are attractive."
"No, I am not."
"I insist that you are, and you will have to trust my opinion." So naturally, I reciprocated the same compliment about him.
Yours sincerely, Anne M. Frank
WEDNESDAY, MARCH 29, 1944
Dearest Kitty,
Mr.

During a Dutch broadcast from London, Bolkestein, the Cabinet Minister, announced that a collection of diaries and letters discussing the war would be created post-war. Naturally, there was a great deal of interest in my diary. It is quite fascinating to consider the potential impact of publishing a novel centered around the Secret Annex.

The title itself would give the impression of a detective story, leading people to think so. However, after a decade since the war, it would be quite entertaining for individuals to learn about our experiences as Jews in hiding - our lifestyle, food choices, and conversations. Despite my efforts to provide extensive details about our lives, there remains a limited understanding of who we truly are.

The level of fear experienced by women during air raids is difficult to comprehend. For example, last Sunday, 350 British planes unleashed 550 tons of bombs on IJmuiden, causing houses to shake like blades of grass in the wind. Additionally, there are numerous epidemics wreaking havoc here. It is clear that you are unaware of these circumstances, and it would require significant time to provide a comprehensive description of every detail.

Individuals are required to queue in order to purchase vegetables and various goods; doctors are unable to make house calls due to frequent theft of their vehicles and bicycles; burglaries and thefts have become so prevalent that...

What has caused the Dutch to become so prone to stealing? Even young children, aged eight and eleven, are breaking into people's homes and taking whatever they can get their hands on. The fear of leaving the house for just a few minutes is justified, as one might return to find all their possessions gone.

Each day, the newspapers are brimming with announcements offering rewards for the recovery of stolen items such as typewriters, Persian rugs, electric clocks, fabrics, and more. The electric clocks installed on street corners are taken apart, and public phones are stripped of all their wires. The morale of the Dutch people is likely to be low.

Everyone is experiencing hunger, except for the imitation coffee. The food ration for a week is not enough to last for two days. The invasion is taking a long time to happen, and the men are being transported to Germany. The children are either sick or malnourished, and everyone is dressed in tattered clothes and worn-out shoes. A brand new sole can be purchased for 7.50 guilders on the black market.

In addition, there are very few shoemakers who offer repair services. And if they do, you may have to wait for a long period, around four months, during which your shoes might even get lost. 
However, there is one positive outcome from this situation. As the quality of food declines and the government's rules become more strict, acts of sabotage against the authorities are on the rise. The ration board, police, and other officials are either supporting their fellow citizens or reporting them and sending them to prison.

Thankfully, only a small fraction of the Dutch population is on the incorrect side. 
Yours sincerely, Anne

During our conversation about blood, we unexpectedly veered towards the topic of menstruation and such. He expressed admiration for women, believing that we are resilient to endure the blood loss, including myself. This made me curious about the reasons behind his viewpoint.

MONDAY, APRIL 3, 1944 
My dearest Kitty, 
I want to give you a detailed description of the food situation, which has become a difficult and important matter not only in the Annex, but also in all of Holland, Europe, and beyond. 
During the twenty-one months we've been here, we've experienced numerous "food cycles" - a term you'll understand shortly. A "food cycle" refers to a period when we have only one specific dish or type of vegetable to eat.

We exclusively consumed endive for an extended period of time. We had endive with sand, endive without s, and endive paired with mashed potatoes. We also enjoyed endive-and-mashed potato casserole. Eventually, our diet shifted to spinach, then kohlrabi, salsify, cucumbers, tomatoes, sauerkraut, and so on.

Eating sauerkraut every day for lunch and dinner may not be enjoyable, but when you're really hungry, you'll do whatever it takes. Fortunately, we are currently experiencing a wonderfully pleasant phase where there are no vegetables available.

The lunch menu for the week includes brown beans, split-pea soup, potatoes with dumplings, potato kugel, and, if available, turnip greens or carrots that may not be in the best condition. After that, we return to eating brown beans. Due to a shortage of bread, potatoes are included in every meal, even breakfast, but they are fried slightly. To prepare soup, we use a combination of brown beans, navy beans, potatoes, packages of vegetable soup, chicken soup, and bean soup.
Brown beans are present in all dishes, even the bread. Our dinner always consists of potatoes served with imitation gravy, and luckily we still have beet salad. I must mention the dumplings to you.

Our bread is made using flour, water, and yeast provided by the government. It has a sticky and chewy texture, almost like having rocks in your stomach, but that's okay. The best part is when we get to enjoy a slice of liverwurst and some jam on our bread without any butter.
Despite the challenges we face, we are still breathing and often find joy in the simple pleasures of life. Sincerely, Anne M. Frank. Wednesday, April 5, 1944.

My beloved Kitty, 
I have been questioning the purpose of doing schoolwork for quite some time now. The idea of the war ending still feels distant and unreal, almost like a fantasy. If the war continues beyond September, I have decided not to return to school, as I do not wish to fall two years behind.

Peter consumed my days, occupying my thoughts and dreams until Saturday night. On that dreadful evening, I felt an overwhelming sense of misery. Despite my inner turmoil, I managed to conceal my tears while in Peter's presence. I laughed wholeheartedly with the van Daans as we indulged in lemon punch, projecting an air of cheerfulness and excitement. However, the moment I found myself alone, I knew tears were inevitable. Clad in my nightgown, I sank to the floor and began my prayers with great fervor.

Afterward, I curled up on the cold floor, bringing my knees close to my chest and resting my head on my arms. Tears streamed down my face as I cried uncontrollably. A sudden, loud sob snapped me back to reality, and I hastily suppressed my emotions, afraid of anyone in the neighboring room overhearing. Determined to regain composure, I repeated to myself, "I have to, I have to, I have to..."
I felt stiff from sitting in an unfamiliar position, causing me to lean against the side of the bed. I continued my struggle until almost ten-thirty, at which point I returned to bed.

The relationship has come to an end! 
And now it's truly finished. I have finally come to the realization that I need to focus on my schoolwork in order to avoid ignorance, succeed in life, and pursue my dream of becoming a journalist.

I have confidence in my writing abilities. Some of my stories are quite good, particularly my amusing descriptions of the Secret Annex. Moreover, much of my diary is filled with vibrant and lively details. However, there is a lingering doubt.

It is uncertain if I truly possess talent, as it is yet to be determined. Surprisingly, "Eva's Dream" stands as my most exceptional fairy tale, and what's peculiar is that I have no clue about its origin.
Although some parts of "Cady's Life" are commendable, overall it lacks uniqueness. I am both my biggest supporter and toughest critic, capable of discerning what is good and what is not.

If you don't engage in writing, you cannot fully appreciate its wonders. Previously, I would lament my inability to draw, but now I am thrilled that I can at least write. Even if I lack the skill to write novels or newspaper pieces, I can still write for my own enjoyment. However, my aspirations extend beyond that.

I find it difficult to envision a life where I am solely defined by being a wife and mother, like Mother, Mrs. van Daan, and other women who work tirelessly and then fade into obscurity. I yearn for something more meaningful to dedicate myself to, beyond just a spouse and children.

I desire to lead a purposeful life, unlike the majority of people who may have lived in vain. My aim is to be of value and bring joy to all individuals, regardless of whether I have ever crossed paths with them. I yearn to leave a lasting impact even after I am gone, continuing to exist in some form.

I am extremely thankful to God for blessing me with this gift, allowing me to grow personally and express my innermost thoughts. Writing enables me to release all my worries and troubles, making my sorrows fade away and uplifting my spirits.

I have been given a new lease on life! However, there remains a lingering uncertainty: will I ever possess the ability to create something truly remarkable? Is it within my reach to become a journalist or a writer? My deepest desire is for this to come true, as writing enables me to document every aspect of my thoughts, beliefs, and dreams.

It has been a long time since I last worked on "Cady's Life." Although I have a clear vision of what happens next in my mind, the progress of the story seems to be lacking. There is a possibility that I may never complete it, and it could end up discarded in the waste bin or burned in the stove.

I find it distressing to think that I may not have the ability to write about philosophy at the young age of fourteen and with limited experience. However, I choose to remain optimistic and determined to continue writing. I believe that everything will turn out well. 
Sincerely, 
Anne M.

Dear Kitty,

You inquired about my hobbies and interests, and I am happy to answer, although I must caution you that I have quite a few, so please don't be taken aback. 

Firstly, there is writing, although I don't truly consider it a mere hobby.

Secondly, I enjoy creating genealogical charts.

Best regards,
Frank

I am diligently searching through newspapers, books, and various documents in order to obtain the family trees of the French, German, Spanish, English, Austrian, Russian, Norwegian, and Dutch royal families. I have made considerable advancements with several of them by meticulously taking notes while reading biographies or historical books.

I have gone so far as to transcribe numerous passages on history. Therefore, my third hobby is studying history, and my father has already purchased many books for me. I am eagerly anticipating the day when I can visit the local library and search for the specific information I require.

I am knowledgeable about Greek and Roman mythology, which is number four on my list. Additionally, I possess several books that delve into this subject. I am capable of reciting the names of the nine Muses and the seven romantic interests of Zeus.
I have a thorough knowledge of the wives of Hercules, among other things. I am also passionate about movie stars and collecting family photographs. Reading is another one of my great loves.

I have a strong passion for books that delve into the history of the arts, particularly when it focuses on writers, poets, and painters. While my interest in musicians may develop later, I must admit that I strongly dislike algebra, geometry, and arithmetic.

I love all my other school subjects, but history is the one I enjoy the most! 
Sincerely, Anne M. Frank

Each day, I sense my personal growth and a sense of freedom edging closer. I appreciate the splendor of nature and the kindness of those in my surroundings. Every day, I ponder on this captivating and delightful journey. Considering all this, why would I ever feel hopeless?

On Friday, May 5, 1944, I, Anne M. Frank, write to you, dear Kitty, to share my current situation. My father is disappointed in me as he expected me to cease my nightly visits to the upper floor after our conversation last Sunday.
He doesn't want any of that "Ne cking" happening. I dislike that word. Discussing it was already unpleasant enough - why does he have to make me feel worse!
I plan to speak with him today. Margot provided me with some valuable advice. Here is a rough idea of what I would like to express:

Father, I believe you are anticipating an explanation from me, so I will provide one. It seems that you are not satisfied with my behavior and had higher expectations of me, perhaps hoping for greater self-control. It is possible that you desire me to conform to the typical behavior of a fourteen-year-old. However, I must respectfully disagree with that notion.

Since we arrived here in July 1942 until recently, I have faced numerous challenges. It is difficult to express the extent of my nightly tears, unhappiness, and despair, as well as the overwhelming loneliness I experienced. It is because of these reasons that I longed to escape to the upstairs. However, I have now reached a stage where I no longer rely on the assistance of my mother or anyone else for support.

Becoming as independent as I am today was not an overnight process. It required enduring struggles, shedding tears, and putting in considerable effort. Regardless of whether you choose to laugh or doubt my journey, I remain indifferent.

I acknowledge my independence and believe that I do not owe you an explanation for my actions. However, I want to be transparent with you to ensure that you do not perceive any secrecy on my part. Nonetheless, I am solely answerable to myself.

When I faced difficulties, everyone, including you, turned a blind eye and deaf ear, refusing to assist me. Instead, I consistently received reprimands for being too loud. My only intention in being loud was to distract myself from constant misery.

I was excessively confident in order to avoid acknowledging the inner voice within me. For the past year and a half, I have been pretending and putting up a facade consistently. I have never expressed any discontent or shown my true self, and now...

I have emerged victorious! I now possess independence in both my physical and mental state. I no longer rely on a mother figure, and through the challenges I faced, I have become a more resilient individual.

Having come to the realization that it's all over and the victory has been achieved, I desire to pursue my own path, following what feels right to me. Please don't see me solely as a fourteen-year-old, as the challenges I have faced have matured me. I have no intentions of remorse for my decisions; I will conduct myself in accordance with my own judgement. Kindly understand that no amount of gentle persuasion can deter me from proceeding upstairs.
You have two options: either prohibit it or have faith in me unconditionally. Regardless of your decision, please refrain from bothering me. Sincerely, Anne M.

Frank

On Sunday morning, May 7, 1944, Dearest Kitty, Father and I had an extensive conversation yesterday afternoon. I cried excessively, and he also shed tears.

Kitty, do you remember what he told me? He mentioned, "Throughout my life, I've received numerous letters, yet none have been as deeply hurtful as this one. It's difficult for me to comprehend, considering the immense love and support I have received from my parents." Can you please provide an alternative wording for this message?

You, who have always had supportive parents by your side, constantly ready to assist you, and who have consistently stood up for you, regardless of the circumstances. You speak of not needing to justify your actions to us! You believe that you have been treated unfairly and abandoned to figure things out on your own.

Anne, it seems you have mistakenly misrepresented us. Although it may not have been your intention, the way you expressed it has caused us great harm. Anne, we are perplexed by this allegation as we genuinely believe we have done nothing to warrant such criticism.

Oh, I have utterly failed. This is the most terrible thing I have ever done in my entire existence. I resorted to using my tears as a means to impress others and appear significant in order to earn their respect.

I have experienced my fair share of unhappiness, and everything I stated about Mother is accurate. However, it was extremely cruel to accuse Pim, who is so kind and has done everything for me. It is actually beneficial that someone has finally humbled me and shattered my pride, as I have been excessively self-satisfied.

Mistress Anne's actions are not always commendable. It is truly deplorable for someone to intentionally inflict pain upon someone they claim to love, making them the most contemptible individuals. What truly brings me shame is how Father has chosen to forgive me. He expressed his intention to discard the letter and has been treating me kindly, as if he were the one at fault.

Anne, it is important for you to start learning and stop criticizing others. Instead of constantly blaming them, it is time for you to take the initiative and make a fresh start. We all experience sorrow at some point in our lives, and I have certainly experienced my fair share at my age.

I have been pretending, although I was not fully conscious of it. I have experienced feelings of solitude, but I have never reached a point of desperation, unlike my Father. There was a time when he went out into the street with a knife, seeking to end his life.
I have never crossed that boundary. I should feel a profound sense of shame, and I do. The past cannot be changed, but I can strive to prevent it from recurring.
Now that I have Peter by my side, starting all over shouldn't be a challenge. With his support, I am confident that I can accomplish it. I no longer feel isolated as I have someone supporting me.

I am loved by him, and I love him in return. Additionally, I have my collection of books, my writing, and my diary. I do not consider myself to be extremely unattractive or unintelligent. I possess a positive and cheerful attitude, and I strive to cultivate a strong character. However, Anne, it is evident that you were aware of the unkind and false nature of your letter, yet you felt a sense of pride in it.

Once again, I will look to my father as my role model and strive to better myself. 
Sincerely, Anne M. Frank
