Van Daan made a joke that was offensive to racial purity. After leaving my papers in Peter's care, I returned downstairs. I asked Margot, who was going through the books, which ones were damaged.
Margot mentioned "Algebra." However, fortunately, my algebra book wasn't completely ruined. I wish it had landed directly in the vase.

I have never despised a book as much as that one. Inside the first page, I can see the names of at least twenty girls who had it before me. It is aged, with a yellowed appearance, and contains numerous scribbles, words crossed out, and revisions.

When I'm in a very angry mood again, I plan to rip that thing apart completely! 
Yours sincerely, Anne M. Frank 
Monday, May 22, 1944 
Dear Kitty, 
On May 20th, Father unfortunately lost his bet and had to give Mrs. five jars of yogurt.

Van Daan: 
Despite the anticipation, the invasion has yet to commence. It is safe to assert that the topic of invasion is consuming the thoughts and conversations of Amsterdam, Holland, and even the entire western coast of Europe, extending as far as Spain. People are engaging in constant debates, placing bets, and discussing the invasion incessantly.

The suspense is reaching an intense level; not all those we consider to be "good" Dutch individuals have remained confident in the English. Some do not view the English bluff as a brilliant strategic maneuver. Instead, they desire tangible actions - grand and heroic deeds. Nobody seems to consider that the British are fighting for their own nation and their own citizens. Everyone believes it is England's responsibility to swiftly rescue Holland.

What obligations do the English have towards us? What actions have the Dutch taken to deserve the assistance they clearly anticipate so generously? Oh dear, it appears that the Dutch are quite mistaken.

Despite their confident demeanor, the English cannot be solely blamed for the war, as there are numerous other countries, both large and small, that are currently under German occupation. The British are not attempting to provide excuses; it is true that they were unaware during the years when Germany was rearming itself, but the same can be said for other countries, particularly those bordering Germany. England and the rest of the world have learned that ignoring the reality of the situation is ineffective, and now they all, especially England, are facing the consequences of their avoidance.

Every country has its reasons for sacrificing its men, and England is no different. The time for invasion, liberation, and freedom will eventually come, but England will be the one to decide when. Unfortunately, it is disheartening to learn that many individuals have altered their perception of Jews, causing us great sorrow and disappointment.

We have received reports that anti-Semitism has emerged in groups where it was previously unimaginable. This information has greatly impacted all of us on a profound level. While we can comprehend the reasons behind this hatred, perhaps even considering them as a part of human nature, it is crucial to acknowledge that it remains morally unjustifiable.

Christians believe that Jews are disclosing their secrets to Germans, resulting in the suffering and punishment of their helpers. This assertion holds some truth. However, it is important to consider both perspectives. If Christians were in the same situation, would they behave any differently?

Is it realistic to expect anyone, regardless of their religious background, to stay silent when faced with pressure from Germany? It is widely acknowledged that remaining silent under such circumstances is nearly impossible, so why do people expect the Jews to do the impossible? There are rumors circulating in underground groups that the German Jews who fled to Holland before the war and have now been relocated to Poland should not be permitted to come back here. Can you please reword this passage?

After being granted asylum in Holland, they should return to Germany once Hit ler is no longer in power. This statement raises questions about the prolonged and challenging war we are engaged in. We are constantly reminded that our fight is for the values of freedom, truth, and justice.

The war is not even over, and already there is division and discrimination against Jews. It is truly disheartening to see that the age-old saying, "What one Christian does is his own responsibility, what one Jew does reflects on all Jews," is once again being proven true. 
To be frank, I struggle to comprehend how the Dutch, who are known for being good, honest, and upright people, can pass judgment on us in the manner that they do. They judge us - the most oppressed, unfortunate, and pitiable people in the world.

I have a single hope: that this anti-Semitism will eventually fade away, and the Dutch people will demonstrate their true character by remaining steadfast in their belief in justice. The current situation is unjust, and I pray that it is only temporary. If this dreadful threat is ever acted upon, the small number of Jews remaining in Holland will be forced to leave. We will also have to gather our belongings and depart from this wonderful country that once welcomed us with open arms but now rejects us.
I have a deep affection for Holland. I used to have the hope that it would become like a second homeland to me, especially after losing my own. This hope still persists within me!

Dear Kitty,

I wanted to let you know that Bep is now engaged. It wasn't really a surprise to any of us, but none of us are really happy about it. 

Sincerely,
Anne M. Frank

Although Bertus may be a nice and athletic young man, it seems that Bep does not have romantic feelings for him. In my opinion, this is a sufficient reason to advise against their marriage. Bep is ambitious and striving for success, but Bertus seems to be holding her back. He is a laborer with no apparent interests or aspirations, and I believe this will not bring happiness to Bep. I understand that Bep wants to resolve her indecision, as she previously tried to end things with Bertus four weeks ago but ended up feeling even more miserable.
She sent him a letter and is now betrothed. The engagement is influenced by a few factors, primarily Bep's ailing father who holds a great fondness for Bertus.

Next, she is the eldest among the Vosku ijl girls and her mother playfully mocks her for being single. Additionally, she recently celebrated her twenty-fourth birthday, which holds significant importance for Bep.

My mother suggested that it may have been preferable for Bep to have had a romantic involvement with Bertus. Personally, I empathize with Bep and comprehend her feelings of solitude. Nevertheless, due to Bertus being in hiding or living covertly, they can only consider marriage once the war is over.

In addition, they are completely broke and have no possessions or savings for the future. It is truly unfortunate for Bep, whom we all hope will have a better outcome. I can only wish that Bertus will become a better person under her guidance, or that Bep will find a different man who can truly value her.
Every day, there is always something happening. This morning, Mr.

Van Hoeven has been arrested for harboring two Jews in his residence. This news comes as a significant blow, as it not only puts those unfortunate individuals in a precarious position once more, but it is also distressing for Mr.

Van Hoeven. The world has been completely disrupted. The individuals with the highest moral standards are being forcibly relocated to concentration camps, prisons, and isolated cells, while those with the lowest moral character dominate over people of all ages and economic statuses.

One person is apprehended for engaging in black market activities, while another is discovered for sheltering Jews or other unfortunate individuals. Unless one is a Nazi, it is impossible to predict the consequences they may face each day.

Van Hoeven's absence is also a significant setback for us. It is unrealistic to expect Bep to transport such large quantities of potatoes all the way here, and it is unfair to burden her with that task. Therefore, our only option is to reduce our consumption of potatoes. I will share our plan with you, but I must warn you that it will not improve our living conditions here.

My mother has decided that we will not have breakfast. Instead, we will have hot cereal and bread for lunch, and fried potatoes for dinner. If we can, we will also include vegetables or lettuce in our meals once or twice a week. This limited food plan means we will be hungry, but it is better than getting caught.

My beloved Kitty, after much anticipation, I am finally able to find solace at my table, positioned by the crack in the window frame, where I can pour out my thoughts and express everything that is on my mind.

I am currently experiencing a level of misery that surpasses anything I have felt in months. Even after the break-in incident, I didn't feel as completely shattered, both emotionally and physically. On one side, there is the recent news concerning Mr. [name].

In Van Hoeven, there is extensive discussion about the Jewish question, the long-awaited invasion, the terrible food, the tense atmosphere, and my disappointment in Peter. However, there are also positive moments such as Bep's engagement, the Pentecost reception, the presence of flowers, Mr. Kugler's birthday, and enjoyable experiences like cakes and stories about cabarets, movies, and concerts.

There is always a significant gap, a vast divide, that exists. It is a constant shift between finding humor in the hidden aspects of life on one day, and experiencing fear, tension, and despair that is evident on our faces on the next day (and there are numerous such days). This applies to both Miep and Mr. [last name].

Miep acknowledges that Kugler bears the heaviest burden on behalf of all of us, including those in hiding. She recognizes the immense responsibility he carries for the eight of us, which at times becomes so overwhelming that he is almost unable to communicate due to the built-up tension and stress.

Kleiman and Bep are also very attentive to us, but they have the ability to temporarily forget about the Annex, even if it's just for a short while. They have their own concerns to occupy their thoughts, such as Mr. Kleiman's health and Bep's uncertain engagement.

However, they also engage in activities outside of their work, such as going out and spending time with friends, and living their lives like ordinary individuals. This allows them to temporarily relieve the tension they experience, even if it is only for a short period. In contrast, we have never experienced such relief from the constantly oppressive and unbearable weight that has been pressing down on us for the past two years. We wonder how much longer we will have to endure this. Additionally, the drains have become clogged once again.

We are unable to run water, or if we do, it is only a small amount; we cannot flush the toilet, so we must rely on a toilet brush; and we have been storing our dirty water in a large clay jar. We can cope for today, but what will occur if the plumber is unable to fix it alone? The Sanitation Department cannot come until Tuesday.

Miep kindly gave us a loaf of raisin bread with the words "Happy Pentecost" written on it. However, it feels like she may be teasing us, as our emotions and concerns are anything but joyful. The incident with the van Hoeven has left us all even more fearful. Once again, we find ourselves speaking in hushed tones, cautious in our every action.
If the police were able to force open the door there, it is likely they could do the same here as well! What would our course of action be if we ever find ourselves in that situation?
I cannot write that down; however, the question persists in my mind today. Instead of fading away, all the fear I have ever experienced is haunting me, causing immense terror.

At eight this evening, I had to venture downstairs by myself to use the bathroom. Everyone else was occupied listening to the radio, so there was no one else downstairs. Although I aspired to be courageous, I felt uneasy about the situation.

It was difficult. I consistently feel more secure upstairs compared to being in that enormous, quiet house. Whenever I am alone and hear those strange muffled sounds coming from upstairs and the honking of car horns outside, I have to quickly remind myself of my surroundings to avoid feeling frightened.
Miep's behavior towards us has improved significantly since she spoke with Father.

I haven't shared this information with you yet, but one afternoon Miep approached Father looking flustered and asked if we believed they were also affected by the prevailing anti-Semitism. Father was taken aback and swiftly reassured her, but some of Miep's doubt has remained.

Currently, they are undertaking additional tasks on our behalf and demonstrating a greater concern for our difficulties, although it is important not to burden them with our problems. Truly, they are exceptional individuals of high moral character. I have repeatedly pondered whether it would have been more advantageous if we had not chosen to hide, if we were no longer alive and did not have to endure this suffering, particularly in order to spare the others from bearing this weight.

However, the idea of death still unsettles us. We continue to cherish life, as we have not yet lost touch with the essence of our natural surroundings, and we maintain a sense of optimism, continuously hoping for something more.
I anxiously anticipate something occurring soon, even if it is an air raid.

This anxiety is truly unbearable, there is nothing more crushing than this feeling. We long for the end to arrive, no matter how cruel it may be, just so we can finally determine if we will emerge as winners or losers. 
Sincerely, Anne M.

Frank 
WEDNESDAY, MAY 31, 1944 
My dearest Kitty, 
I apologize for not writing to you over the past few days. The scorching heat made it impossible for me to hold my fountain pen, rendering me unable to write. Additionally, on Friday, there was an issue with the drains, but thankfully, they were repaired on Saturday by Mrs. [Last Name].

In the afternoon, Kleiman paid us a visit and shared plenty of information about Jopiej. It was mentioned that she and Jacque van Maarsen both belong to the same hockey club. On Sunday, Bep stopped by to check if there had been any break-ins and ended up staying for breakfast. On Monday, which was a holiday due to Pentecost, Mr. [last name not provided] did something.

Gies took on the role of the Annex watchman and on Tuesday, we were finally given permission to open the windows. It was a rare occurrence to have a Pentecost weekend that was as stunning and balmy as this one. Perhaps "sweltering" would be a more fitting description.

The hot weather in the Annex is absolutely unbearable. To give you an insight into the countless grievances, let me provide a brief description of these scorching days. 
On Saturday, although we initially exclaimed, "What splendid weather!" in the morning, it quickly turned into a nightmare.

In the afternoon, we remarked that the temperature was not as high as before, as we had to close the windows due to the wind. On Sunday, we complained about how unbearable the heat was, with the butter melting and no cool spot to be found in the house. The bread was drying out, the milk was turning sour, and we couldn't open the windows. We felt suffocated while everyone else seemed to be enjoying their Pentecost. This account is based on Mrs. [person's last name].

On Monday, I found myself complaining about my sore feet, lack of fashionable clothing, and the discomfort of doing the dishes in the hot weather. The grumbling persisted from morning till night, making it an unpleasant day. Personally, I have a strong dislike for hot temperatures.

I am grateful that the wind has picked up today while the sun is still shining. 
Yours sincerely, Anne M. Frank 
FRIDAY, JUNE 2, 1944 J 
Dear Kitty, 
If you happen to go to the attic, it would be wise to bring an umbrella, preferably a large one! This is to shield yourself from unexpected "household showers." There is a Dutch saying that goes: "High and dry, safe and sound," but unfortunately, it does not hold true during wartime (guns!) and for people in hiding (cat box!). 
Could you please rephrase this passage?

Mouschi has developed a habit of urinating on newspapers or in the gaps of the floorboards, causing us to be concerned about the potential mess and unpleasant odor. Similarly, the new cat Moortje in the warehouse is also experiencing the same issue. Anyone who has had a cat that is not properly trained can understand the unpleasant smells that fill our home, aside from the scents of pepper and thyme.

I have a fresh solution for feeling anxious during gunfire: Whenever the sound of shooting becomes loud, find the closest wooden staircase. Begin running up and down the stairs, purposely stumbling at least once. The noise of your footsteps and the sounds of your falls, along with any scratches you may receive, will drown out the sound of the shooting. This way, you won't have any reason to be concerned about it.

I have personally applied this magical formula and achieved remarkable results! Sincerely, Anne M. Frank. Monday, June 5, 1944. 
My dear Kitty, 
There are new challenges arising in the Annex.
Dussel's surrender led to the division of butter, while also fostering a strong bond between him and Mrs.

Van Daan, engaging in flirtations, exchanging kisses, and sharing friendly little smiles. Dussel is starting to yearn for the company of a woman. The van Daans fail to understand the reason behind baking a spice cake for Mr.
When we are unable to celebrate our own birthdays, it can sometimes lead to feelings of pettiness. The overall mood upstairs is not good.

Dussel was found in possession of brewer's yeast tablets, while we are without any. 
Rome has been captured by the Fifth Army. The city remains unharmed and untouched by bombings.

This text highlights some concerning aspects regarding the availability of food during Hitler's regime. It mentions a scarcity of potatoes and vegetables, as well as the presence of mold on a loaf of bread.

Scharminkeltje, the new warehouse cat, has an aversion to pepp er. She prefers to sleep in the cat box and uses the wood shavings as her designated bathroom spot. It's challenging to accommodate her preferences.
The weather is unfavorable. There is ongoing bombing in Pas de Calais and the west coast of France. There is a lack of interest in purchasing dollars.
Gold has become even more uninteresting. We can now see the bottom of our black moneybox. What will we rely on for income next month?

My beloved Kitty, 
At twelve, the BBC declared, "This day is D Day." 
Today is the day. The invasion has commenced!

At eight o'clock this morning, the British announced that there had been intense aerial attacks on Calais, Boulogne, Le Havre, Cherbourg, and the usual area of Pas de Calais. In addition, as a safety measure for those living in the occupied territories, all individuals residing within twenty miles from the coast were advised to be ready for bombardments. Whenever feasible, the British will distribute pamphlets one hour before the attacks occur.
As reported by German news, British paratroopers have arrived on the shores of France. "British naval vessels are currently in combat with German naval forces."

According to the BBC, the Annex reached the conclusion during breakfast at nine that this is a trial landing, similar to the one that took place two years ago in Dieppe. The BBC broadcasted in various languages, including German, Dutch, and French, at ten, stating that the invasion has started. 
Could you please rephrase this text?

This is the actual invasion taking place. At eleven, Supreme Commander General Dwight Eisenhower delivered a speech which was broadcasted by the BBC in German. Simultaneously, the BBC also broadcasted the same message in English, stating, "This is 0 Day." General Eisenhower addressed the French people, informing them that although intense fighting will ensue, victory will follow. Kindly rephrase this passage.

In the English BBC broadcast at 1 o'clock, it was announced that the year 1944 would be the year of absolute triumph. Wishing good luck, the broadcast reported that a staggering number of 11,000 planes were busy shuttling troops and conducting bombing missions in enemy territory, while 4,000 landing craft and small boats were constantly arriving in the region between Cherbourg and Le Havre. Furthermore, English and American troops were already actively involved in intense combat.

The speeches were delivered by Gerbrandy, the Prime Minister of Belgium, King Haakon of Norway, de Gaulle of France, the King of England, and, finally, Churchill. There was a great uproar in the Annex! Could this truly be the start of the eagerly anticipated liberation? 
Kindly rephrase this passage.
Will the liberation, the subject of so much discussion, ever become a reality that seems too incredible, almost like a fairytale? Can we expect victory in this year, 1944? The answer remains unknown.

In the presence of hope, life persists. It instills within us renewed bravery and revitalizes our strength. To endure the numerous fears, hardships, and forthcoming suffering, we must summon our courage.

Now, it is crucial to stay calm and determined, to endure hardships without complaint! France, Russia, Italy, and even Germany may express their pain, but we have not reached that point yet! Oh, Kitty, the most exciting aspect of the invasion is the belief that help is coming from our friends.

For a considerable time, we have suffered under the oppressive and menacing actions of the Germans. Therefore, the idea of having friends and finding salvation holds immense significance for us. It is not only the Jews who are affected, but also Holland and all of occupied Europe. Margot suggests that there is a possibility of resuming school in October or September.
I, Anne M. Frank, will keep you updated with the latest news.
Straw and rubber dummies were dropped behind German lines from the air last night and this morning. As soon as they touched the ground, they detonated. Numerous instances of this occurred.

Paratroopers, with their faces camouflaged to remain invisible in the darkness, also touched down. The French coastline was subjected to an onslaught of 5,500 tons of bombs throughout the night, followed by the arrival of the initial landing craft at six in the morning. Presently, a staggering count of 20,000 aircraft were engaged in the operation.

The German coastal batteries were demolished prior to the landing, resulting in the establishment of a small bridgehead. Despite unfavorable weather conditions, everything is progressing smoothly. Both the army and the people are united in their determination and optimism. 
Friday, June 9, 1944 
My dearest Kitty, 
I am thrilled to share the wonderful news of the invasion with you!

Bayeux, a coastal village in France, has been captured by the Allies who are now engaged in combat for the city of Caen. Their objective is evidently to sever the peninsula where Cherbourg is situated. Each evening, war correspondents provide updates on the challenges faced, the bravery displayed, and the unwavering determination of the army in the battle.

In order to obtain their stories, they accomplish incredible tasks. Some of the injured individuals who have already returned to England also shared their experiences on the radio. Despite the unfavorable weather conditions, the planes continue to fly smoothly in both directions.

According to the BBC, it was reported that Churchill had expressed a desire to personally join the troops on D Day, but Eisenhower and the other generals were successful in persuading him otherwise. It is quite remarkable to consider the bravery of an older man, who must be at least seventy years old. 
The level of excitement in our area has somewhat subsided, although we all remain hopeful that the war will ultimately come to an end before the year is over.

Finally! Mrs. van Daan's incessant complaining has become intolerable; now that she is unable to drive us insane with her invasion, she spends the entire day whining and grumbling about the unfavorable weather.

If only we could place her in the loft and douse her with a bucket of cold water! All the occupants of the Annex, with the exception of Mr. van Daan and Peter, have read the Hungarian Rhapsody trilogy, which is a biography of Franz Liszt, the renowned composer, piano virtuoso, and child prodigy.

I find it quite fascinating, although in my opinion, the focus on women is a bit excessive. While Liszt was undoubtedly the greatest and most renowned pianist of his time, it is worth noting that he was also quite a womanizer, even in his later years. He had numerous affairs with Countess Marie d' Agoult, Princess Carolyne Sayn- Wittgenstein, dancer Lola Montez, pianists Agnes Kingworth and Sophie Menter, Circassian princess Olga Janina, Baroness Olga Meyendorff, actress Lilla (whose last name escapes me), and many others. The sections of the book that delve into music and other artistic aspects are far more captivating.

The individuals referenced include Schumann, Clara Wieck, Hector Berlioz, Johannes Brahms, Beethoven, Joachim, Richard Wagner, Hans von Bulow, Anton Rubinstein, Frederic Chopin, Victor Hugo, Honore de Balzac, Hiller, Hummel, Czerny, Rossini, Cherubini, Paganini, Mendelssohn, and many others. Kindly provide alternative phrasing for this passage.

Liszt seemed to possess admirable qualities, displaying generosity and humility, although he had an excessive amount of vanity. He selflessly assisted others, prioritizing art above all else, and had a great fondness for cognac and women. Liszt was a compassionate individual who couldn't stand seeing tears, behaving like a true gentleman and always willing to help others. Money held no interest for him as he genuinely cared about religious freedom and the well-being of the world. 
Sincerely, Anne M.

Dear Kit, 
I just turned fifteen and received several gifts for my birthday. Among them were Springer's five-volume art history book, a set of underwear, two belts, a handkerchief, two jars of yogurt, a jar of jam, two small honey cookies, a botany book from my parents, a gold bracelet from Margot, a sticker album from the van Daans, Biomalt and sweet peas from Dussel, candy from Miep, candy and notebooks from Bep, and the best gift of all: the book Maria Theresa and three slices of full-cream cheese from Mr. Kugler.

Peter presented me with a beautiful assortment of peonies; however, he struggled to find the perfect gift. The ongoing invasion is progressing remarkably well, despite the unfavorable weather conditions: heavy rainfall, strong winds, and rough seas. Churchill, Smuts, Eisenhower, and Arnold paid a visit to the French villages that the British successfully seized and freed.

Churchill, aboard a torpedo boat, participated in the shelling of the coast. Like numerous men, he appears to lack knowledge of fear, which is an admirable quality! Assessing the Dutch's mood is challenging from our current location at Fort Annex.

It is evident that many individuals are pleased that the British, who were previously idle, have now started working diligently. Those who argue against being occupied by the British fail to recognize their unfairness. Their argument essentially states that England should engage in combat, endure hardship, and sacrifice its citizens in order to free Holland and other occupied nations.

Subsequently, it is imperative for the British to withdraw from Holland. They must sincerely apologize to all the occupied nations, return the Dutch East Indies to its rightful sovereignty, and then retreat, leaving England in a weakened and impoverished state. It is astonishing how foolish they are. Surprisingly, there are also numerous Dutch individuals who align themselves with this idiocy.
What would have happened to Holland and its neighboring countries if...

If England had chosen to sign a peace treaty with Germany, as it had ample opportunity to do, Holland would have likely become a part of Germany, putting an end to its existence as an independent country. It is ironic that many Dutch people who hold a disdainful view of the British, mocking England and its older generation in government, while also despising the Germans, deserve to be jolted out of their contradictory beliefs, much like how one would fluff up a pillow.

Perhaps that would help organize their confused minds! Desires, ideas, blame, and criticism are all swirling around in my thoughts. I am not as arrogant as many perceive me to be; I am well aware of my flaws and weaknesses, perhaps even more than others. However, there is one distinction: I am determined to transform, have already made significant changes, and will continue to do so!
I often find myself questioning why everyone perceives me as pushy and overly knowledgeable. Is it possible that I truly come across as arrogant? Is it me who possesses arrogance, or is it them?

I understand that it may seem unbelievable, but I won't disregard the last sentence. It may not be as absurd as it appears. Mrs. van Daan and Dussel, the two individuals who accuse me the most, are widely recognized for their lack of intelligence and, to put it bluntly, their stupidity.

Individuals who lack intelligence often struggle to tolerate when others outperform them; notable instances of this can be observed in the behavior of Mrs. van Daan and Dussel, who both exhibit this characteristic.

Van D. believes I am unintelligent because my level of suffering from this ailment is not as severe as hers. She perceives me as assertive because she herself is even more assertive. She considers my dresses to be too short because hers are even shorter. Additionally, she views me as a know-it-all because she excessively discusses topics she has no knowledge about, whereas I speak less but possess more understanding. The same can be said for Dussel.

However, one of my favorite sayings that I often use is "Where there's smoke there's fire," and I must admit that I have a tendency to act like a know-it-all. 

The challenging aspect of my personality is that I tend to scold and criticize myself much more than anyone else does. Even when my mother offers her advice, it adds to the already overwhelming pile of sermons, leaving me feeling hopeless. As a result, I find myself talking back and contradicting everyone, until the familiar refrain of "No one understands me!" inevitably emerges. 

This phrase has become a part of who I am, and although it may appear unlikely, there is a grain of truth in it.

At times, I find myself overwhelmed by self-reproach and yearn for a comforting word that can assist me in overcoming these feelings. It would be incredibly helpful to have someone who truly acknowledges the importance of my emotions. Unfortunately, I have yet to encounter that individual, so I must continue my search.

I sense your curiosity about Peter, don't I, Kit? It's undeniable that Peter has deep feelings for me, although not in a romantic way, but rather as a friend. His fondness for me continues to strengthen with each passing day, yet some unknown obstacle is preventing us from progressing, and I am uncertain of its nature.

At times, I question if my intense longing for him was exaggerated. However, this is not the case as I still yearn for him just as desperately when I am unable to be in his presence for a day or two. Peter possesses kindness and goodness, yet it is difficult to ignore the ways in which he has let me down.

Although I am not a fan of his aversion to religion and his table conversations, among other things, I am still confident that we will uphold our agreement to never argue. Peter is a person who values peace, is accepting, and incredibly laid-back.

He allows me to express many things to him that he would never tolerate from his mother. He is actively working to correct his mistakes and maintain his affairs in good order. However, I wonder why he conceals his true feelings and never grants me entry to his innermost thoughts.

Although he is much more closed off than I am, I have learned from experience that even the most uncommunicative individuals eventually desire someone to confide in. Both Peter and I have spent a significant amount of time in contemplation at the Annex. We frequently engage in discussions about the future, the past, and the present. However, as I mentioned before, I yearn for genuine connection, knowing that it is possible.

Has my prolonged absence from the outdoors caused my newfound fascination with nature? There was a time when the beauty of a vibrant blue sky, cheerful birdsong, the glow of moonlight, and the emergence of blossoms didn't capture my attention. However, since I arrived here, things have shifted.

During the Pentecost holiday, on a particularly hot night, I found it difficult to stay awake until eleven-thirty in order to have a solitary view of the moon. Unfortunately, my efforts were futile due to the excessive glare, and I couldn't take the risk of opening a window. On another occasion, a few months ago, I coincidentally found myself upstairs with an open window at night.

I refrained from descending until there was a need for it to be sealed once more. The gloomy and rainy evening, accompanied by the howling wind and swiftly moving clouds, captivated me entirely. It had been a year and a half since I last encountered the night directly. Subsequently, my desire to witness it again surpassed any apprehension I had regarding burglars, a house infested with dark rats, or potential robberies.

I went downstairs alone and gazed out the windows in the kitchen and private office. Nature is often considered beautiful, and many people find solace in sleeping under the starry sky. Even those in hospitals and prisons yearn for the day when they can freely appreciate what nature has to offer. However, our isolation and disconnection from the joys of nature are unparalleled, despite the fact that they can be enjoyed by both the wealthy and the impoverished. It is not just a figment of my imagination; observing the sky, clouds, moon, and stars genuinely brings me a sense of tranquility and optimism.
I find nature to be a superior remedy compared to valerian or bromide. It instills a sense of humility within me and prepares me to confront any adversity with bravery.

Due to unfortunate circumstances, I am usually limited to observing nature through dusty curtains covering dirty windows, with only a few exceptions. This diminishes the joy of looking. Nature is the only thing that cannot be replaced! A persistent question that has always puzzled me is why women have been and continue to be considered inferior to men.

While it is convenient to label this situation as unfair, I am genuinely interested in understanding the underlying cause behind this significant injustice. It is often argued that men have historically held dominance over women due to their superior physical strength, enabling them to provide for their families, procreate, and exert control over their lives.
In the past, women quietly accepted this situation, which was foolish as it only strengthened its roots further. Thankfully, education, employment, and advancements have enlightened women.

Equal rights have been granted in numerous countries, leading many individuals, particularly women, but also men, to recognize the long-standing acceptance of such a situation as deeply flawed. Present-day women aspire to attain complete independence, desiring more than just that.

Women deserve to be respected too! In most societies, men are highly regarded. So, it's only fair that women also receive their fair share of respect. We honor and remember soldiers and war heroes, we celebrate explorers and grant them everlasting fame, and we revere martyrs. But how many people see women as soldiers too?

I was deeply moved by the book Soldiers on the Home Front, which shed light on the stark reality that women often experience more pain, illness, and suffering during childbirth than any war hero ever endures. Surprisingly, despite enduring such hardships, women receive little recognition for their sacrifices. Instead, they are often marginalized when their bodies undergo changes from giving birth, their children eventually grow up and leave, and their physical attractiveness fades away.

Women, who endure struggles and endure pain for the sake of continuing the human population, possess greater strength and bravery compared to all the boastful heroes fighting for freedom! 
I am not suggesting that women should cease having children; in fact, it is natural and should be embraced. What I criticize are our values as a society and the men who fail to recognize the immense challenges and ultimately magnificent role that women play in our society.

I fully support Paul de Kruif's perspective as expressed in this book, where he emphasizes the importance of recognizing that the concept of birth is no longer seen as inevitable and unavoidable in the regions we consider civilized. Men often underestimate the challenges faced by women, as they do not and will never experience the physical burdens associated with childbirth.

I think that in the next century, the belief that it is solely a woman's responsibility to have children will evolve, allowing for a greater appreciation and respect for all women who carry their responsibilities without complaint or pretentiousness. 
Sincerely, Anne M. Frank 
FRIDAY, JUNE 16, 1944 
Dearest Kitty, 
I have encountered new challenges with Mrs. [last name].
Van D. is feeling extremely distressed. She is discussing experiences involving being shot, imprisoned, facing execution, and contemplating suicide.

She feels envious because Peter trusts me with his secrets instead of her. She is upset because Dussel doesn't respond adequately to her attempts to flirt with him. She is also worried that her husband will spend all the money meant for a fur coat on tobacco. She constantly argues, curses, cries, pities herself, laughs, and then repeats the cycle. How can you possibly deal with such a foolish and whining person? Please provide a rephrased version of this text.

She is not taken seriously by anyone, lacks inner strength, constantly complains to everyone, and her manner of walking is quite unimpressive. She appears like a schoolgirl and dresses unfashionably. To make matters worse, Peter is becoming disrespectful, Mr. van Daan is easily irritated, and Mother has become cynical. It seems like everyone is in a state of distress.
The key rule to remember is to find humor in everything and not worry about what others think. While it may seem self-centered, it is actually the only remedy for those experiencing self-pity.
Kugler is attempting to avoid spending four weeks in Alkmaar for work by obtaining a doctor's certificate and a letter from O pekta.

Kleiman is eager for his stomach operation to take place soon. Private phone lines were disconnected from eleven o'clock last night. 
Best regards, 
Anne M.

Frank 
FRIDAY, JUNE 23, 1944 
Dear Kitty, 
There is nothing particularly noteworthy happening here. The British have initiated a full-scale assault on Cherbourg. Pim and Mr. have informed me about it.

We can be confident that we will achieve liberation before October 10. The campaign now involves the participation of the Russians, who initiated their offensive near Vitebsk yesterday. Interestingly, this offensive began exactly three years after the Germans invaded Russia.

Bep's morale has reached a new low. Our potato supply is running dangerously low, so we have decided to ration them out individually, allowing each person to use them as they please. Beginning on Monday, Miep will be taking a week off for some well-deserved vacation.
The X rays have not revealed any findings by Mr. Kleiman's doctors. He is undecided about whether to undergo surgery or allow things to progress naturally.

My beloved Kitty, 
There has been a shift in the atmosphere, and everything is going incredibly smoothly. Today, the cities of Cherbourg, Vitebsk, and Zhlobin were captured.

It is highly likely that they have successfully captured a significant number of men and equipment. Near Cherbourg, five German generals were killed and two were captured. With the acquisition of a harbor, the British now have the ability to bring any desired items onto land.

Just three weeks after the invasion, the entire Cotentin Peninsula has been successfully captured! It is truly an impressive accomplishment considering the continuous rain and storms that have plagued both the Allies and France. However, this unfavorable weather has not deterred the British and American forces from showcasing their strength.

Absolutely! Undoubtedly, the Germans have introduced their extraordinary weapon, but such a small-scale explosive will hardly have a significant impact, except for potentially causing minor harm in England and generating sensational headlines in German newspapers. Nevertheless, once the people in Germany comprehend that the Bolsheviks are genuinely advancing, they will be filled with fear and apprehension.

Are all non-military German women being evacuated, along with their children, from the coastal regions to Groningen, Friesland, and Gelderland provinces? Mussert, the leader of the Dutch National Socialist Party, has stated that if the invasion reaches Holland, he will enlist. Is Mussert, who is referred to as a fat pig, intending to fight?
He had the opportunity to do that in Russia much earlier. Finland rejected a peace offer some time ago, and now the negotiations have once again been terminated. Those fools, they will regret it!

Dear Kitty, 

I am curious to know how much progress we will have made by July 27. 

Yours sincerely, 
Anne M. Frank

The weather has been consistently bad from the first to the thirtieth of June. Do I not pronounce that correctly? Oh, yes, I already have some knowledge of English; just to demonstrate it, I am reading "An Ideal Husband" with the assistance of a dictionary! The war is progressing excellently: Bobruysk, Mogilev, and Orsha have been captured, resulting in many prisoners. Can you please rephrase this text?

Things are going well here. People are feeling better, our extremely positive individuals are succeeding, the van Daans are sneaking around with the sugar, Bep has a different hairstyle, and Miep has a week of vacation. That's the most recent update!
